{"title_page": "Bridget McKenzie", "text_new": "{{short description|Australian politician}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2016}}\n{{Use Australian English|date=January 2016}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| honorific-prefix = [[Australian Senate|Senator]] [[The Honourable]]\n| name = Bridget McKenzie\n| honorific-suffix = \n| image = Bridget McKenzie 2014-01.jpg\n| office = [[National Party of Australia|Deputy Leader of the National Party]]\n| term_start = 7 December 2017\n| term_end = 2 February 2020\n| leader = [[Barnaby Joyce]] <br/ >[[Michael McCormack (Australian politician)|Michael McCormack]]\n| predecessor = [[Fiona Nash]]\n| successor = [[David Littleproud]]\n| office1 = [[Minister for Agriculture (Australia)|Minister for Agriculture]]\n| term_start1 = 29 May 2019\n| term_end1 = 2 February 2020\n| primeminister1 = [[Scott Morrison]]\n| predecessor1 = [[David Littleproud]]\n| successor1 = [[Michael McCormack (Australian politician)|Michael McCormack]]\n| office2 = [[Minister for Regional Services, Decentralisation and Local Government]]\n| term_start2 = 28 August 2018\n| term_end2 = 29 May 2019\n| primeminister2 = [[Scott Morrison]]\n| minister2 = [[Michael McCormack (Australian politician)|Michael McCormack]]\n| predecessor2 = [[John McVeigh (politician)|John McVeigh]]\n| successor2 = [[Mark Coulton]]\n| office3 = [[Minister for Youth and Sport|Minister for Sports]]\n| term_start3 = 20 December 2017\n| term_end3 = 29 May 2019\n| primeminister3 = [[Malcolm Turnbull]]<br/>[[Scott Morrison]]\n| predecessor3 = [[Greg Hunt]]\n| successor3 = [[Richard Colbeck]]\n| office4 = [[Minister for Health (Australia)#List of ministers for rural health|Minister for Rural Health]]<br /> [[Minister for Communications (Australia)#List of ministers for regional communications|Minister for Regional Communications]]\n| term_start4 = 20 December 2017\n| term_end4 = 28 August 2018\n| primeminister4 = [[Malcolm Turnbull]]<br/>[[Scott Morrison]]\n| predecessor4 = [[Fiona Nash]]\n| successor4 = (abolished)\n| title5 = [[Australian Senate|Senator]] for [[Victoria (Australia)|Victoria]]\n| term_start5 = 1 July 2011\n| term_end5 = \n| predecessor5 = [[Julian McGauran]]\n| birth_name = Bridget McKenzie\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1969|12|27|df=y}}\n| birth_place = {{VICcity|Alexandra}}, [[Victoria (Australia)|Victoria]], Australia\n| party = [[National Party of Australia|The Nationals]]\n| alma_mater = [[Deakin University]]\n}}\n'''Bridget McKenzie''' (born 27 December 1969) is an Australian politician. She was [[2010 Australian federal election|elected]] to [[Parliament of Australia|federal parliament]] in 2010 and took her seat as a [[Australian Senate|Senator]] for [[Victoria (Australia)|Victoria]] on 1 July 2011.  She won re-election at the [[2016 Australian federal election|2016 election]].  In December 2017, she was elected deputy leader of the National Party in place of [[Fiona Nash]], who had been ruled [[2017 Australian parliamentary eligibility crisis|ineligible for election]] to the Senate by the [[High Court of Australia|High Court]].  As a consequence of the terms of the Coalition agreement with the [[Liberal Party of Australia|Liberal Party]], Prime Minister [[Malcolm Turnbull]] immediately appointed McKenzie to cabinet as [[Minister for Sport (Australia)|Minister for Sport]], [[Minister for Health (Australia)#List of ministers for rural health|Minister for Rural Health]], and [[Minister for Communications (Australia)#List of ministers for regional communications|Minister for Regional Communications]].  When [[Scott Morrison]] [[2018 Liberal Party of Australia leadership spills|replaced Turnbull]] as Prime Minister, he [[reshuffle]]d the ministry and [[First Morrison Ministry|abolished the latter two positions]]. McKenzie retained the sports portfolio and also became [[Minister for Regional Services, Decentralisation and Local Government]] until the [[2019 Australian federal election|2019 Federal election]], after which she became the first woman to be appointed as [[Minister for Agriculture (Australia)|Minister for Agriculture]].\n\nIn the lead-up to the 2019 election, McKenzie [[Sports rorts affair (2020)|oversaw a controversial $100 million grant program]] that led to claims of [[Pork barrel|pork-barrelling]]. A report by the [[Australian National Audit Office]] stated that the administration of the program \"was not informed by an appropriate assessment process and sound advice.\"  [[Sports Australia]] made determinations as to which applications were most deserving of funding, but the allocation of grants was subsequently determined by ministerial discretion and the Auditor-General's report noted that it was unclear whether this was within McKenzie's legal authority.  The allocations went disproportionately to marginal electorates held by the Coalition or to electorates that the Coalition was targeting in the election and critics alleged she had unlawfully spent taxpayer funds with the aim of improving the coalition's electoral prospects. No evidence was supplied. Morrison ordered an investigation when claims were made that McKenzie had acted with a conflict of interest in directing funding to a club of which she was a member. McKenzie resigned from her positions as Minister for Agriculture and deputy party Leader on 2 February 2020.\n\nPrior to entering politics, McKenzie started a family and then attended [[Deakin University]] as a mature-age student, where she served as the president of the [[Deakin University Student Association|student association]] in 2003.  She stood for the [[House of Representatives (Australia)|House of Representatives]] seat of [[Division of McMillan|McMillan]] at the [[2004 Australian federal election|2004 election]], but was unsuccessful.  Prior to becoming a Senator, McKenzie worked as a school teacher in the [[Gippsland|Gippsland region]] of Victoria and later at [[Monash University]] where she lectured in Education.  Between 2006 and 2009, McKenzie was a junior vice-president of the Victorian branch of the National Party, which she had joined when she was 18 years old. After entering the Senate, McKenzie served as [[List of whips in the Australian Senate|party whip]] from 2013 to 2014.\n\n==Early life==\nMcKenzie was born in [[Alexandra, Victoria]]. She grew up in [[Benalla]], where her mother was a primary school teacher and her father was a dairyman. She attended [[Tintern Grammar]], where she was a house captain and swimming captain. After starting a family, McKenzie began studying at [[Deakin University]] as a mature-age student, completing a double degree in applied science (specialising in human movement) and teaching (specialising in mathematics). She served as the president of the [[Deakin University Student Association]] in 2003.<ref>\"A Degree of Rivalry\", ''[[Sunday Age]]'', 10 August 2003.</ref> McKenzie subsequently taught physical education and mathematics for several years at [[Yarram, Victoria|Yarram Secondary College]], [[Gippsland]]. She later lectured in education at [[Monash University]].<ref>[https://www.aph.gov.au/Senators_and_Members/Parliamentarian?MPID=207825 Senator Bridget McKenzie], Parliament of Australia. Retrieved 19 December 2017.</ref>\n\n==Politics==\n[[File:Bridget McKenzie 2014-02.jpg|thumb|right|McKenzie in November 2014]]\nMcKenzie joined the National Party at the age of 18, and was a junior vice-president of [[National Party of Australia \u2013 Victoria|the Victorian branch]] from 2006 to 2009. She first stood for parliament at the [[2004 Australian federal election|2004 federal election]], unsuccessfully standing for the [[Australian House of Representatives|House of Representatives]] in the [[Division of McMillan]].<ref>[http://australianwomenonline.com/women-in-politics-bridget-mckenzie-national-party-senator-for-victoria/ Women in Politics: Bridget McKenzie, National Party Senator for Victoria], Australian Women Online. Retrieved 18 August 2013. Retrieved 19 December 2017.</ref> At the [[2010 Australian federal election|2010 election]], McKenzie was elected to the [[Australian Senate|Senate]] in the third place on a joint [[Coalition (Australia)|Coalition]] ticket. Her term began on 1 July 2011.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.abc.net.au/elections/federal/2010/guide/svic-results.htm |title=Senate Results - Victoria - 2010 Federal Election |accessdate=12 September 2010}}</ref>\n\nMcKenzie was her party's [[List of whips in the Australian Senate|Senate whip]] from September 2013 to June 2014. She was elected deputy leader to [[Barnaby Joyce]] in December 2017, replacing [[Fiona Nash]] after her [[2017 Australian parliamentary eligibility crisis|disqualification from parliament]] due to dual citizenship.<ref>[http://www.smh.com.au/federal-politics/political-news/gunloving-senator-bridget-mckenzie-elected-barnaby-joyces-new-deputy-20171206-h00awc.html Gun-loving senator Bridget McKenzie elected Barnaby Joyce's new deputy], ''[[The Sydney Morning Herald]]'', 8 December 2017. Retrieved 19 December 2017.</ref> Under the terms of the Coalition Agreement with the Liberals, McKenzie was  elevated to [[Cabinet of Australia|cabinet]] as [[Minister for Sport (Australia)|Minister for Sport]], [[Minister for Health (Australia)#List of ministers for rural health|Minister for Rural Health]], and [[Minister for Communications (Australia)#List of ministers for regional communications|Minister for Regional Communications]].<ref name=\"Turnbull2nd-4thAR\">{{cite press release|quote=Deputy Nationals Leader Bridget McKenzie joins Cabinet as Minister for Sport, Rural Health and Regional Communications. Bridget has long campaigned for better services for regional communities.|url=https://www.pm.gov.au/media/ministerial-arrangements-2|title=Ministerial Arrangements|date=19 December 2017|publisher=[[Government of Australia]]|author=Turnbull, Malcolm|authorlink=Malcolm Turnbull|accessdate=3 February 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180313005337/https://www.pm.gov.au/media/ministerial-arrangements-2#|archive-date=13 March 2018|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nWhen [[Scott Morrison]] became prime minister in August 2018, McKenzie was appointed [[Minister for Regional Services, Decentralisation and Local Government]]. She also retained the sport portfolio.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.aph.gov.au/Senators_and_Members/Parliamentarian?MPID=207825|title=Senator the Hon Bridget McKenzie|publisher=Parliament of Australia|access-date=5 October 2019}}</ref> After the Coalition retained office at the [[2019 Australian federal election|2019 election]], she was appointed [[Minister for Agriculture (Australia)|Minister for Agriculture]], the first woman to hold the position.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.farmonline.com.au/story/6182682/bridget-mckenzie-australias-first-female-agriculture-minister/|title=Bridget McKenzie Australia's first female Agriculture Minister|publisher=Farm Online|date=26 May 2019|access-date=5 October 2019}}</ref>\n\nMcKenzie is a shooting enthusiast, and is chair of the Parliamentary Friends of Shooting.<ref>[http://www.smh.com.au/federal-politics/political-news/meet-bridget-mckenzie-the-turnbull-government-senator-out-to-change-your-mind-about-guns-20151025-gkhubu.html Meet Bridget McKenzie, the Turnbull government senator out to change your mind about guns], ''[[The Sydney Morning Herald]]'', 26 October 2015. Retrieved 19 December 2017.</ref> She is opposed to [[Same-sex marriage in Australia|same-sex marriage]], and publicly campaigned for the \"No\" vote in the [[Australian Marriage Law Postal Survey]].<ref>[http://www.bendigoadvertiser.com.au/story/3136550/mckenzie-against-same-sex-marriage-supports-conscience-vote/ McKenzie against same sex marriage, supports conscience vote], ''[[Bendigo Advertiser]]'', 10 June 2015. Retrieved 19 December 2017.</ref> McKenzie's gay younger brother confronted her on her views in a letter to the ''[[Bendigo Advertiser]]'' and on the panel discussion program ''[[Q&A (Australian talk show)|Q&A]]''.<ref>[http://www.smh.com.au/entertainment/tv-and-radio/qa-recap-coalition-senator-bridget-mckenzie-confronted-by-gay-brother-over-plebiscite-20160912-gret2z.html Q&A recap: Coalition senator Bridget McKenzie confronted by gay brother over plebiscite], ''The Sydney Morning Herald'', 13 September 2016. Retrieved 19 December 2017.</ref><ref>[http://www.abc.net.au/news/2015-06-13/gay-brother-of-nationals-senator-hits-out-at-sisters-comments/6543844 Brother of Nationals senator Bridget McKenzie hits out against sister's comments on same-sex marriage], ABC News, 13 June 2015. Retrieved 19 December 2017.</ref>\n=== Pork barrelling scandal ===\n{{main|Sports rorts affair (2020)}}\nIn January 2020, McKenzie was widely accused of [[Pork barrel|pork-barrelling]]<ref>{{cite news |last=Speers |first=David |date=2020-01-16 |title=Bridget McKenzie's sport grant cash splash is a particularly brazen example of pork-barrelling |url=https://www.abc.net.au/news/2020-01-16/bridget-mckenzie-saga-pork-barrelling-brazen-example/11874224|work=ABC News|location=Australia|access-date=2020-01-20}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Wray |first=Michael |date=2020-01-15 |title=National Audit Office found 60 per cent of grants failed to meet minimum requirements|url=https://www.couriermail.com.au/news/queensland/queensland-government/national-audit-office-found-60-per-cent-of-grants-failed-to-meet-minimum-requirements/news-story/988481e674bb948cb170133a0d3fba90|work=The Courier Mail|access-date=2020-01-20}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Burke|first=Kelly|date=2020-01-16|title=Morrison government accused of pork barrelling over $100m 'sports rorts' scandal|url=https://7news.com.au/sport/morrison-government-on-the-defence-over-alleged-100-million-sports-rort-c-650018|work=7 News|access-date=2020-01-20}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|date=2020-01-18|title=Pork barrelling comes at a cost |url=https://www.theaustralian.com.au/commentary/editorials/pork-barrelling-comes-at-a-cost/news-story/a039cf708b66c60144b6b9b4920b9b56|work=The Australian|access-date=2020-01-20}}</ref> after a report by the [[Australian National Audit Office |Commonwealth auditor-general]] found that a $100&nbsp;million sports grant program which she oversaw in the lead-up to the [[2019 Australian federal election]] was administered in a way that \"was not informed by an appropriate assessment process and sound advice\". The auditor-general's report noted that it was not clear what the legal authority for the particular allocation of grants was.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Speers|first1=David|title=Bridget McKenzie's sport grant cash splash is a particularly brazen example of pork-barrelling|url=https://www.abc.net.au/news/2020-01-16/bridget-mckenzie-saga-pork-barrelling-brazen-example/11874224|accessdate=2020-01-16|work=ABC News|location=Australia|date=2020-01-16}}</ref> \n\nA disproportionately high percentage of funds were allocated to sporting clubs in marginal [[Coalition (Australia)|Coalition]] electorates. One Adelaide rugby union club was awarded a $500,000 grant under the scheme for new female change rooms, despite not fielding a women's team since 2018 when it was embroiled in a sexism controversy. The club, located in the marginal Coalition-held seat of [[Division of Sturt|Sturt]], was awarded the scheme's maximum available grant just weeks before the election.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Martin|first1=Sarah|date=2020-01-24|title=Sports grants: rugby club gets $500,00 for female change rooms but has no women's team|url= https://www.theguardian.com/australia-news/2020/jan/24/sports-grants-rugby-club-gets-funding-for-female-change-rooms-but-has-no-womens-team/|work=The Guardian|access-date=2020-01-24}}</ref> A football club in the marginally held Coalition seat of [[Division of Brisbane|Brisbane]]<!--With a 55:45 majority, Division of Brisbane is hardly a marginal--> was given $150,000 for a project that had already been funded.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Karp |first1=Paul| last2= Remeikis |first2= Amy|date=2020-01-28|title=Sports grants: Brisbane football club given $150,000 for project that was already funded|url= https://www.theguardian.com/australia-news/2020/jan/28/sports-grants-brisbane-football-club-given-150000-for-project-that-was-already-funded/|work=The Guardian|access-date=2020-01-28}}</ref> More than $1&nbsp;million in grants were allocated to sports clubs with links to clubs Coalition MPs as members or patrons: three linked to Indigenous affairs minister [[Ken Wyatt]], one tied to treasurer and deputy Liberal leader [[Josh Frydenberg]], and two associated with senator [[Sarah Henderson]].<ref>{{cite news|last1=Karp|first1=Paul|last2=Knaus|first2=Christopher|date=2020-01-22|title=Sport grants: more than $1m given to nine clubs linked to Coalition MPs|url= https://www.theguardian.com/australia-news/2020/jan/22/sport-grants-more-than-1m-given-to-nine-clubs-linked-to-coalition-mps|work=The Guardian|access-date=2020-01-28}}</ref> Nationals leader Michael McCormack's son's football club in the NSW Riverina also received a $147,000 grant under the program. In some cases, the funds were presented as oversized novelty cheques by the Liberal candidate for the seat in question, rather than by the sitting member.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Burgess|first1=Katie|last2=Lawson|first2=Kirsten|date=2020-01-17|title=Pressure grows on Bridget McKenzie over sports grants as more footage appears of candidates offering giant cheques|url= https://www.canberratimes.com.au/story/6585194/pressure-grows-on-mckenzie-as-more-footage-appears-of-candidates-offering-giant-cheques/|work=The Canberra Times|access-date=2020-01-22}}</ref> \n\n====Calls for resignation====\n\nThe Opposition called for McKenzie to resign from the federal ministry because of the bias in the funding allocated. She maintained that \"no project that received funding was not eligible to receive it\" and that \"no rules were broken in this program\".<ref name=\"abc-20200116\">{{cite news|last1=Norman|first1=Jane |last2=Worthington|first2=Brett|title=Bridget McKenzie facing calls to quit after auditors condemn 'biased' sports cash splash |url=https://www.abc.net.au/news/2020-01-16/sports-club-angry-at-bridget-mckenzie-government-grants/11873320|accessdate=2020-01-16|work=ABC News|location=Australia|date=2020-01-16}}</ref> The Leader of the Opposition [[Anthony Albanese]] stated that what McKenzie had done \"fails every test\" and she must be sacked.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.smh.com.au/politics/federal/it-fails-every-test-albanese-says-pm-must-sack-bridget-mckenzie-20200122-p53tlm.html|title='It fails every test': Albanese says PM must sack Bridget McKenzie|first=Rob|last=Harris|date=21 January 2020|website=The Sydney Morning Herald}}</ref>\n\nIn 1993, [[Ros Kelly]], the Labor Sports Minister in the [[Keating government]] resigned under almost identical circumstances in what came to be known as the [[Sports rorts affair|Sports Rorts affair]].\n\nMore than 70 per cent of ''[[The Australian Financial Review|Australian Financial Review]]'' readers said that McKenzie should resign over the scandal.<ref>{{cite news|author=Seo, Bo|url=https://www.afr.com/politics/federal/afr-readers-say-bridget-mckenzie-has-to-go-20200127-p53v09|title=AFR readers say Bridget McKenzie has to go\n|work=The Australian Financial Review|date=27 January 2020|accessdate=27 January 2020}}</ref>\n\n====Government response====\n\nThe government steadfastly supported McKenzie throughout the scandal. [[Prime Minister of Australia|Prime Minister]] [[Scott Morrison]]<ref>{{cite news|author=Karp, Paul|url=https://www.theguardian.com/australia-news/2020/jan/20/scott-morrison-backs-bridget-mckenzie-in-sports-grants-scandal-and-will-clarify-legal-issues|title=Scott Morrison backs Bridget McKenzie in sports grants scandal and will \u2018clarify\u2019 legal issues|work=The Guardian|date=20 January 2020|accessdate=3 February 2020}}</ref>, Michael McCormack<ref>{{cite news|author=Martin, Sarah|url=https://www.theguardian.com/australia-news/2020/jan/24/sports-grants-michael-mccormack-stands-by-bridget-mckenzie-saying-she-has-done-outstanding-job|title=Sports grants: Michael McCormack stands by Bridget McKenzie, saying she has done \u2018outstanding job\u2019|work=The Guardian|date=24 January 2020|accessdate=3 February 2020}}</ref>, [[Peter Dutton]]<ref>{{cite news|author=Tillet, Andrew|url=https://www.afr.com/politics/federal/dutton-argues-there-s-no-reason-for-bridget-mckenzie-s-scalp-20200124-p53ubr|title=Dutton argues there's no reason for Bridget McKenzie's scalp|work=The Australian Financial Review|date=24 January 2020|accessdate=2 February 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theaustralian.com.au/subscribe/news/1/?sourceCode=TAWEB_WRE170_a&dest=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.theaustralian.com.au%2Fnation%2Fpolitics%2Fgovernment-will-not-listen-to-twitter-peter-dutton-defends-bridget-mckenzie-over-sports-grants%2Fnews-story%2Fe4909b24757aa7f9be1572e871ee7e79&memtype=anonymous&mode=premium&nk=b2afb22f55a195c6b679971d08b42f8a-1580779300|title=Government will not listen to twitter: Peter Dutton defends Bridget McKenzie over sports grants|website=[[The Australian]]|date= |accessdate=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.afr.com/politics/federal/dutton-argues-there-s-no-reason-for-bridget-mckenzie-s-scalp-20200124-p53ubr|title=Dutton argues there's no reason for Bridget McKenzie's scalp|date=24 January 2020|website=Australian Financial Review}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://9now.nine.com.au/today/bridget-mckenzie-quits-government-reaction/01d930c6-0973-4585-bf45-8fedb303fb15|title=McKenzie resignation no embarrassment, insists Dutton|website=9now.nine.com.au}}</ref> and other high-profile Coalition ministers repeatedly spoke out in her defence.<ref name=\"auto\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/australia-news/2020/feb/02/sports-rort-dutton-backs-beleaguered-mckenzie-saying-ive-got-confidence-in-bridget|title=Sports rort: Dutton backs beleaguered McKenzie saying 'I've got confidence in Bridget'|author=Murphy, Katharine|date=2 February 2020|work=Guardian Australia}}</ref>\n\nFollowing the revelation that McKenzie awarded a $36,000 grant to a regional Victorian shooting club without declaring that she was a member, on 22 January 2020 Morrison referred the matter to the Commonwealth Auditor-General and the Secretary of the [[Department of the Prime Minister and Cabinet (Australia)|Department of the Prime Minister and Cabinet]] for advice in relation to the conduct of ministerial standards.<ref name=\"auto1\">{{cite news|author=Harris, Rob|url=https://www.smh.com.au/politics/federal/clip-reveals-mckenzie-gave-club-a-grant-after-joining-as-member-20200122-p53ttl.html|title=PM orders conflict of interest review of McKenzie's shooting grant|work=The Sydney Morning Herald|date=22 January 2020|accessdate=22 January 2020}}</ref> On 29 January, Morrison attempted to distance himself from the scandal after being asked questions at a National Press Club meeting. Morrison was asked why his office had approved an extra $42.5&nbsp;million for the sports grants scheme in March 2019, but did not explain.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.abc.net.au/news/2020-01-29/scott-morrison-distances-self-sports-grants-bridget-mckenzie/11909940|title=Scott Morrison distances himself from sports grants scandal plaguing his Government|first=Brett|last=Worthington|date=29 January 2020|website=ABC News}}</ref>\n\nThe report by the Secretary of the Department of Prime Minister and Cabinet determined that McKenzie had breached the ministerial code of conduct and, on 2 February, she tendered her resignation as Minister for Agriculture and Deputy Leader of her party.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.9news.com.au/national/bridget-mckenzie-resigns-over-sports-grant-scandal-australian-politics/f5c1f458-8d67-414a-8115-89f68b62767a|title=Bridget McKenzie resigns from cabinet over sports grant saga|website=www.9news.com.au}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.abc.net.au/news/2020-02-02/bridget-mckenzie-quits-over-ministerial-standards-breach/11896610|title=Bridget McKenzie quits frontbench over report she breached ministerial standards|work=[[ABC News (Australia)|ABC News]]|date=2 February 2020|accessdate = 2 February 2020|location=Australia}}</ref>\n\n==Other controversies==\n\nIn 2017, McKenzie was accused of using parliamentary travel entitlements for personal benefit, in a weekend trip to the [[Gold Coast, Queensland|Gold Coast]] in September 2014.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.theaustralian.com.au/national-affairs/barnabys-new-deputy-silent-on-weekend-trip-to-gold-coast/news-story/3a6d0f4d3c45393f6ea984a5105db709|title=Nationals new deputy silent on weekend trip to Gold Coast|date=2017-12-14|work=The Australian|access-date=2017-12-17|language=en-US}}</ref> Also questioned was a February 2017 trip to [[Sydney]] to speak at a Shooting Australia awards ceremony, which was claimed as \"electorate business\"; media reports suggested that it did not fall under the usual category of parliamentary business, and the city of Sydney is not located in the state of Victoria which Bridget represents.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.smh.com.au/federal-politics/political-news/nationals-deputy-bridget-mckenzie-charged-taxpayers-to-attend-shooting-awards-20171216-h05vqh.html|title=Nationals deputy Bridget McKenzie charged taxpayers to attend shooting awards|date=2017-12-16|work=The Sydney Morning Herald|access-date=2017-12-17|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\nMcKenzie's electorate office was in the regional city of [[Bendigo]], and she was described in media headlines{{by whom?|date=December 2017}} as \"Bendigo-based\" on a number of occasions<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bendigoadvertiser.com.au/story/5106185/bridget-mckenzie-named-new-national-party-deputy-leader/|title=Bridget McKenzie named new National Party deputy leader|date=2017-12-07|website=Bendigo Advertiser|language=en|access-date=2020-01-24}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thecourier.com.au/story/5106778/bridget-mckenzie-named-new-national-party-deputy-leader/|title=Bridget McKenzie named new National Party deputy leader|date=2017-12-07|website=The Courier|language=en|access-date=2020-01-24}}</ref>. In 2018, after maintaining the office in Bendigo as \"a National Party campaign office\" for some months following her ascension to Cabinet, McKenzie relocated her electorate office to Wodonga, some 250km away in the federal electorate of [[Division of Indi|Indi]], which led to rumours she would contest the seat,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.mailtimes.com.au/story/5832039/bridget-mckenzie-rules-out-mallee-contest-uncertain-about-indi/|title=Bridget McKenzie rules out Mallee contest, uncertain about Indi|last=Johnston|first=David|date=2019-01-01|website=The Wimmera Mail-Times|language=en|access-date=2020-01-31}}</ref> at the [[2019 Australian federal election|2019 federal election]] but eventually declined to do so. This ultimately cost taxpayers more than $500,000.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bendigoadvertiser.com.au/story/6258260/mckenzie-bills-taxpayers-530000-for-new-office/|title=McKenzie bills taxpayers $530,000 for new office|last=Johnston|first=David|date=2019-07-04|website=Bendigo Advertiser|language=en|access-date=2020-01-31}}</ref> In 2016 it was noted that her primary residence was a flat in the inner-Melbourne suburb of [[Elwood, Victoria|Elwood]], and she stayed in hotels when she visited Bendigo.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.abc.net.au/centralvic/programs/central_victoria_mornings/?site=centralvic/|title=Nationals Senator Bridget McKenzie responds to criticism she lives in the inner-city|date=2017-10-12|work=[[Australian Broadcasting Corporation]]|access-date=2017-12-18|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nMcKenzie has four children from her first marriage to Tim Edwards, a former Police officer and now massage therapist in Ballarat, which ended in divorce <ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.smh.com.au/federal-politics/political-news/meet-bridget-mckenzie-the-turnbull-government-senator-out-to-change-your-mind-about-guns-20151025-gkhubu.html|title=Meet Bridget McKenzie, the Turnbull government senator out to change your mind about guns|date=2015-10-26|work=Sydney Morning Herald|access-date=2017-11-02|language=en-US}}</ref> She was subsequently in a long-distance relationship with [[David Bennett (New Zealand politician)|David Bennett]], a member of the [[New Zealand Parliament]] and both are members of their respective countries' National Parties.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.nzherald.co.nz/nz/news/article.cfm?c_id=1&objectid=11772755|title=Trans-Tasman relations: Long-distance love for Hamilton East MP David Bennett, who confirms he is in a relationship with Australian senator|date=2016-12-24|work=NZ Herald|access-date=2017-11-02|language=en-US}}</ref><ref>[http://www.theaustralian.com.au/national-affairs/bridget-mckenzie-new-zealand-enchants-another-national/news-story/69088f1b43bc6dabf6fddfda5c5e184b Bridget McKenzie: New Zealand enchants another National], ''[[The Australian]]'', 9 December 2017. Retrieved 19 December 2017.</ref>\n\n==See also==\n{{stack|{{portal|Biography|Politics|Australia}}}}\n* [[Sports rorts affair (2020)]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.bridgetmckenzie.com.au/ Official website]\n* [https://theyvoteforyou.org.au/people/senate/victoria/bridget_mckenzie Summary of parliamentary voting for Senator Bridget McKenzie on TheyVoteForYou.org.au]\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-off}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[David Littleproud]]|as=Minister for Agriculture and Water Resources}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Minister for Agriculture (Australia)|Minister for Agriculture]]|years=2019\u20132020}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Michael McCormack (Australian politician)|Michael McCormack]]}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[John McVeigh (politician)|John McVeigh]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Minister for Regional Services, Decentralisation and Local Government]]|years=2018\u20132019}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Mark Coulton]]}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Greg Hunt]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Minister for Sport (Australia)|Minister for Sport]]|years=2017\u20132019}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Richard Colbeck]]}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Fiona Nash]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Minister for Health (Australia)#List of ministers for rural health|Minister for Rural Health]]|years=2017\u20132018}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Greg Hunt]]|as=Minister for Health}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Fiona Nash]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Minister for Communications (Australia)#List of ministers for regional communications|Minister for Regional Communications]]|years=2017\u20132018}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Mitch Fifield]]|as=Minister for Communications and the Arts}}\n{{s-ppo}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Fiona Nash]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=Deputy Leader of the [[National Party of Australia]]|years=2017\u20132020}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[David Littleproud]]}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Nigel Scullion]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=Leader of the [[National Party of Australia]] in the Senate|years=2017\u2013present}}\n{{s-inc}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{Australian Senators}}\n{{Second Turnbull Ministry}}\n{{First Morrison Ministry}}\n{{Second Morrison Ministry}}\n{{National Party of Australia}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:McKenzie, Bridget}}\n[[Category:1969 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Abbott Government]]\n[[Category:National Party of Australia members of the Parliament of Australia]]\n[[Category:Members of the Australian Senate]]\n[[Category:Members of the Australian Senate for Victoria]]\n[[Category:Women members of the Australian Senate]]\n[[Category:Deakin University alumni]]\n[[Category:Monash University faculty]]\n[[Category:Turnbull Government]]\n[[Category:Australian people of Scottish descent]]\n[[Category:People from Alexandra, Victoria]]\n[[Category:21st-century Australian politicians]]\n[[Category:21st-century Australian women politicians]]\n[[Category:Government ministers of Australia]]\n[[Category:Women government ministers of Australia]]\n[[Category:Members of the Cabinet of Australia]]\n[[Category:Morrison Government]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Australian politician}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2016}}\n{{Use Australian English|date=January 2016}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| honorific-prefix = [[Australian Senate|Senator]] [[The Honourable]]\n| name = Bridget McKenzie\n| honorific-suffix = \n| image = Bridget McKenzie 2014-01.jpg\n| office = [[National Party of Australia|Deputy Leader of the National Party]]\n| term_start = 7 December 2017\n| term_end = 2 February 2020\n| leader = [[Barnaby Joyce]] <br/ >[[Michael McCormack (Australian politician)|Michael McCormack]]\n| predecessor = [[Fiona Nash]]\n| successor = [[David Littleproud]]\n| office1 = [[Minister for Agriculture (Australia)|Minister for Agriculture]]\n| term_start1 = 29 May 2019\n| term_end1 = 2 February 2020\n| primeminister1 = [[Scott Morrison]]\n| predecessor1 = [[David Littleproud]]\n| successor1 = [[Michael McCormack (Australian politician)|Michael McCormack]]\n| office2 = [[Minister for Regional Services, Decentralisation and Local Government]]\n| term_start2 = 28 August 2018\n| term_end2 = 29 May 2019\n| primeminister2 = [[Scott Morrison]]\n| minister2 = [[Michael McCormack (Australian politician)|Michael McCormack]]\n| predecessor2 = [[John McVeigh (politician)|John McVeigh]]\n| successor2 = [[Mark Coulton]]\n| office3 = [[Minister for Youth and Sport|Minister for Sports]]\n| term_start3 = 20 December 2017\n| term_end3 = 29 May 2019\n| primeminister3 = [[Malcolm Turnbull]]<br/>[[Scott Morrison]]\n| predecessor3 = [[Greg Hunt]]\n| successor3 = [[Richard Colbeck]]\n| office4 = [[Minister for Health (Australia)#List of ministers for rural health|Minister for Rural Health]]<br /> [[Minister for Communications (Australia)#List of ministers for regional communications|Minister for Regional Communications]]\n| term_start4 = 20 December 2017\n| term_end4 = 28 August 2018\n| primeminister4 = [[Malcolm Turnbull]]<br/>[[Scott Morrison]]\n| predecessor4 = [[Fiona Nash]]\n| successor4 = (abolished)\n| title5 = [[Australian Senate|Senator]] for [[Victoria (Australia)|Victoria]]\n| term_start5 = 1 July 2011\n| term_end5 = \n| predecessor5 = [[Julian McGauran]]\n| birth_name = Bridget McKenzie\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1969|12|27|df=y}}\n| birth_place = {{VICcity|Alexandra}}, [[Victoria (Australia)|Victoria]], Australia\n| party = [[National Party of Australia|The Nationals]]\n| alma_mater = [[Deakin University]]\n}}\n'''Bridget McKenzie''' (born 27 December 1969) is an Australian politician. She was [[2010 Australian federal election|elected]] to [[Parliament of Australia|federal parliament]] in 2010 and took her seat as a [[Australian Senate|Senator]] for [[Victoria (Australia)|Victoria]] on 1 July 2011.  She won re-election at the [[2016 Australian federal election|2016 election]].  In December 2017, she was elected deputy leader of the National Party in place of [[Fiona Nash]], who had been ruled [[2017 Australian parliamentary eligibility crisis|ineligible for election]] to the Senate by the [[High Court of Australia|High Court]].  As a consequence of the terms of the Coalition agreement with the [[Liberal Party of Australia|Liberal Party]], Prime Minister [[Malcolm Turnbull]] immediately appointed McKenzie to cabinet as [[Minister for Sport (Australia)|Minister for Sport]], [[Minister for Health (Australia)#List of ministers for rural health|Minister for Rural Health]], and [[Minister for Communications (Australia)#List of ministers for regional communications|Minister for Regional Communications]].  When [[Scott Morrison]] [[2018 Liberal Party of Australia leadership spills|replaced Turnbull]] as Prime Minister, he [[reshuffle]]d the ministry and [[First Morrison Ministry|abolished the latter two positions]]. McKenzie retained the sports portfolio and also became [[Minister for Regional Services, Decentralisation and Local Government]] until the [[2019 Australian federal election|2019 Federal election]], after which she became the first woman to be appointed as [[Minister for Agriculture (Australia)|Minister for Agriculture]].\n\nIn the lead-up to the 2019 election, McKenzie [[Sports rorts affair (2020)|oversaw a controversial $100 million grant program]] that led to claims of [[Pork barrel|pork-barrelling]]. A report by the [[Australian National Audit Office]] stated that the administration of the program \"was not informed by an appropriate assessment process and sound advice.\"  [[Sports Australia]] made determinations as to which applications were most deserving of funding, but the allocation of grants was subsequently determined by ministerial discretion and the Auditor-General's report noted that it was unclear whether this was within McKenzie's legal authority.  The allocations went disproportionately to marginal electorates held by the Coalition or to electorates that the Coalition was targeting in the election and critics alleged she had unlawfully spent taxpayer funds with the aim of improving the coalition's electoral prospects. No evidence was supplied. Morrison ordered an investigation when claims were made that McKenzie had acted with a conflict of interest in directing funding to a club of which she was a member. McKenzie resigned from her positions as Minister for Agriculture and deputy party Leader on 2 February 2020.\n\nPrior to entering politics, McKenzie started a family and then attended [[Deakin University]] as a mature-age student, where she served as the president of the [[Deakin University Student Association|student association]] in 2003.  She stood for the [[House of Representatives (Australia)|House of Representatives]] seat of [[Division of McMillan|McMillan]] at the [[2004 Australian federal election|2004 election]], but was unsuccessful.  Prior to becoming a Senator, McKenzie worked as a school teacher in the [[Gippsland|Gippsland region]] of Victoria and later at [[Monash University]] where she lectured in Education.  Between 2006 and 2009, McKenzie was a junior vice-president of the Victorian branch of the National Party, which she had joined when she was 18 years old. After entering the Senate, McKenzie served as [[List of whips in the Australian Senate|party whip]] from 2013 to 2014.\n\n==Early life==\nMcKenzie was born in [[Alexandra, Victoria]]. She grew up in [[Benalla]], where her mother was a primary school teacher and her father was a dairyman. She attended [[Tintern Grammar]], where she was a house captain and swimming captain. After starting a family, McKenzie began studying at [[Deakin University]] as a mature-age student, completing a double degree in applied science (specialising in human movement) and teaching (specialising in mathematics). She served as the president of the [[Deakin University Student Association]] in 2003.<ref>\"A Degree of Rivalry\", ''[[Sunday Age]]'', 10 August 2003.</ref> McKenzie subsequently taught physical education and mathematics for several years at [[Yarram, Victoria|Yarram Secondary College]], [[Gippsland]]. She later lectured in education at [[Monash University]].<ref>[https://www.aph.gov.au/Senators_and_Members/Parliamentarian?MPID=207825 Senator Bridget McKenzie], Parliament of Australia. Retrieved 19 December 2017.</ref>\n\n==Politics==\n[[File:Bridget McKenzie 2014-02.jpg|thumb|right|McKenzie in November 2014]]\nMcKenzie joined the National Party at the age of 18, and was a junior vice-president of [[National Party of Australia \u2013 Victoria|the Victorian branch]] from 2006 to 2009. She first stood for parliament at the [[2004 Australian federal election|2004 federal election]], unsuccessfully standing for the [[Australian House of Representatives|House of Representatives]] in the [[Division of McMillan]].<ref>[http://australianwomenonline.com/women-in-politics-bridget-mckenzie-national-party-senator-for-victoria/ Women in Politics: Bridget McKenzie, National Party Senator for Victoria], Australian Women Online. Retrieved 18 August 2013. Retrieved 19 December 2017.</ref> At the [[2010 Australian federal election|2010 election]], McKenzie was elected to the [[Australian Senate|Senate]] in the third place on a joint [[Coalition (Australia)|Coalition]] ticket. Her term began on 1 July 2011.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.abc.net.au/elections/federal/2010/guide/svic-results.htm |title=Senate Results - Victoria - 2010 Federal Election |accessdate=12 September 2010}}</ref>\n\nMcKenzie was her party's [[List of whips in the Australian Senate|Senate whip]] from September 2013 to June 2014. She was elected deputy leader to [[Barnaby Joyce]] in December 2017, replacing [[Fiona Nash]] after her [[2017 Australian parliamentary eligibility crisis|disqualification from parliament]] due to dual citizenship.<ref>[http://www.smh.com.au/federal-politics/political-news/gunloving-senator-bridget-mckenzie-elected-barnaby-joyces-new-deputy-20171206-h00awc.html Gun-loving senator Bridget McKenzie elected Barnaby Joyce's new deputy], ''[[The Sydney Morning Herald]]'', 8 December 2017. Retrieved 19 December 2017.</ref> Under the terms of the Coalition Agreement with the Liberals, McKenzie was  elevated to [[Cabinet of Australia|cabinet]] as [[Minister for Sport (Australia)|Minister for Sport]], [[Minister for Health (Australia)#List of ministers for rural health|Minister for Rural Health]], and [[Minister for Communications (Australia)#List of ministers for regional communications|Minister for Regional Communications]].<ref name=\"Turnbull2nd-4thAR\">{{cite press release|quote=Deputy Nationals Leader Bridget McKenzie joins Cabinet as Minister for Sport, Rural Health and Regional Communications. Bridget has long campaigned for better services for regional communities.|url=https://www.pm.gov.au/media/ministerial-arrangements-2|title=Ministerial Arrangements|date=19 December 2017|publisher=[[Government of Australia]]|author=Turnbull, Malcolm|authorlink=Malcolm Turnbull|accessdate=3 February 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180313005337/https://www.pm.gov.au/media/ministerial-arrangements-2#|archive-date=13 March 2018|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nWhen [[Scott Morrison]] became prime minister in August 2018, McKenzie was appointed [[Minister for Regional Services, Decentralisation and Local Government]]. She also retained the sport portfolio.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.aph.gov.au/Senators_and_Members/Parliamentarian?MPID=207825|title=Senator the Hon Bridget McKenzie|publisher=Parliament of Australia|access-date=5 October 2019}}</ref> After the Coalition retained office at the [[2019 Australian federal election|2019 election]], she was appointed [[Minister for Agriculture (Australia)|Minister for Agriculture]], the first woman to hold the position.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.farmonline.com.au/story/6182682/bridget-mckenzie-australias-first-female-agriculture-minister/|title=Bridget McKenzie Australia's first female Agriculture Minister|publisher=Farm Online|date=26 May 2019|access-date=5 October 2019}}</ref>\n\nMcKenzie is a shooting enthusiast, and is chair of the Parliamentary Friends of Shooting.<ref>[http://www.smh.com.au/federal-politics/political-news/meet-bridget-mckenzie-the-turnbull-government-senator-out-to-change-your-mind-about-guns-20151025-gkhubu.html Meet Bridget McKenzie, the Turnbull government senator out to change your mind about guns], ''[[The Sydney Morning Herald]]'', 26 October 2015. Retrieved 19 December 2017.</ref> She is opposed to [[Same-sex marriage in Australia|same-sex marriage]], and publicly campaigned for the \"No\" vote in the [[Australian Marriage Law Postal Survey]].<ref>[http://www.bendigoadvertiser.com.au/story/3136550/mckenzie-against-same-sex-marriage-supports-conscience-vote/ McKenzie against same sex marriage, supports conscience vote], ''[[Bendigo Advertiser]]'', 10 June 2015. Retrieved 19 December 2017.</ref> McKenzie's gay younger brother confronted her on her views in a letter to the ''[[Bendigo Advertiser]]'' and on the panel discussion program ''[[Q&A (Australian talk show)|Q&A]]''.<ref>[http://www.smh.com.au/entertainment/tv-and-radio/qa-recap-coalition-senator-bridget-mckenzie-confronted-by-gay-brother-over-plebiscite-20160912-gret2z.html Q&A recap: Coalition senator Bridget McKenzie confronted by gay brother over plebiscite], ''The Sydney Morning Herald'', 13 September 2016. Retrieved 19 December 2017.</ref><ref>[http://www.abc.net.au/news/2015-06-13/gay-brother-of-nationals-senator-hits-out-at-sisters-comments/6543844 Brother of Nationals senator Bridget McKenzie hits out against sister's comments on same-sex marriage], ABC News, 13 June 2015. Retrieved 19 December 2017.</ref>\n=== Pork barrelling scandal ===\n{{main|Sports rorts affair (2020)}}\nIn January 2020, McKenzie was widely accused of [[Pork barrel|pork-barrelling]]<ref>{{cite news |last=Speers |first=David |date=2020-01-16 |title=Bridget McKenzie's sport grant cash splash is a particularly brazen example of pork-barrelling |url=https://www.abc.net.au/news/2020-01-16/bridget-mckenzie-saga-pork-barrelling-brazen-example/11874224|work=ABC News|location=Australia|access-date=2020-01-20}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Wray |first=Michael |date=2020-01-15 |title=National Audit Office found 60 per cent of grants failed to meet minimum requirements|url=https://www.couriermail.com.au/news/queensland/queensland-government/national-audit-office-found-60-per-cent-of-grants-failed-to-meet-minimum-requirements/news-story/988481e674bb948cb170133a0d3fba90|work=The Courier Mail|access-date=2020-01-20}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Burke|first=Kelly|date=2020-01-16|title=Morrison government accused of pork barrelling over $100m 'sports rorts' scandal|url=https://7news.com.au/sport/morrison-government-on-the-defence-over-alleged-100-million-sports-rort-c-650018|work=7 News|access-date=2020-01-20}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|date=2020-01-18|title=Pork barrelling comes at a cost |url=https://www.theaustralian.com.au/commentary/editorials/pork-barrelling-comes-at-a-cost/news-story/a039cf708b66c60144b6b9b4920b9b56|work=The Australian|access-date=2020-01-20}}</ref> after a report by the [[Australian National Audit Office |Commonwealth auditor-general]] found that a $100&nbsp;million sports grant program which she oversaw in the lead-up to the [[2019 Australian federal election]] was administered in a way that \"was not informed by an appropriate assessment process and sound advice\". The auditor-general's report noted that it was not clear what the legal authority for the particular allocation of grants was.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Speers|first1=David|title=Bridget McKenzie's sport grant cash splash is a particularly brazen example of pork-barrelling|url=https://www.abc.net.au/news/2020-01-16/bridget-mckenzie-saga-pork-barrelling-brazen-example/11874224|accessdate=2020-01-16|work=ABC News|location=Australia|date=2020-01-16}}</ref> \n\nA disproportionately high percentage of funds were allocated to sporting clubs in marginal [[Coalition (Australia)|Coalition]] electorates. One Adelaide rugby union club was awarded a $500,000 grant under the scheme for new female change rooms, despite not fielding a women's team since 2018 when it was embroiled in a sexism controversy. The club, located in the marginal Coalition-held seat of [[Division of Sturt|Sturt]], was awarded the scheme's maximum available grant just weeks before the election.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Martin|first1=Sarah|date=2020-01-24|title=Sports grants: rugby club gets $500,00 for female change rooms but has no women's team|url= https://www.theguardian.com/australia-news/2020/jan/24/sports-grants-rugby-club-gets-funding-for-female-change-rooms-but-has-no-womens-team/|work=The Guardian|access-date=2020-01-24}}</ref> A football club in the marginally held Coalition seat of [[Division of Brisbane|Brisbane]]<!--With a 55:45 majority, Division of Brisbane is hardly a marginal--> was given $150,000 for a project that had already been funded.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Karp |first1=Paul| last2= Remeikis |first2= Amy|date=2020-01-28|title=Sports grants: Brisbane football club given $150,000 for project that was already funded|url= https://www.theguardian.com/australia-news/2020/jan/28/sports-grants-brisbane-football-club-given-150000-for-project-that-was-already-funded/|work=The Guardian|access-date=2020-01-28}}</ref> More than $1&nbsp;million in grants were allocated to sports clubs with links to clubs Coalition MPs as members or patrons: three linked to Indigenous affairs minister [[Ken Wyatt]], one tied to treasurer and deputy Liberal leader [[Josh Frydenberg]], and two associated with senator [[Sarah Henderson]].<ref>{{cite news|last1=Karp|first1=Paul|last2=Knaus|first2=Christopher|date=2020-01-22|title=Sport grants: more than $1m given to nine clubs linked to Coalition MPs|url= https://www.theguardian.com/australia-news/2020/jan/22/sport-grants-more-than-1m-given-to-nine-clubs-linked-to-coalition-mps|work=The Guardian|access-date=2020-01-28}}</ref> Nationals leader Michael McCormack's son's football club in the NSW Riverina also received a $147,000 grant under the program. In some cases, the funds were presented as oversized novelty cheques by the Liberal candidate for the seat in question, rather than by the sitting member.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Burgess|first1=Katie|last2=Lawson|first2=Kirsten|date=2020-01-17|title=Pressure grows on Bridget McKenzie over sports grants as more footage appears of candidates offering giant cheques|url= https://www.canberratimes.com.au/story/6585194/pressure-grows-on-mckenzie-as-more-footage-appears-of-candidates-offering-giant-cheques/|work=The Canberra Times|access-date=2020-01-22}}</ref> \n\n====Calls for resignation====\n\nThe Opposition called for McKenzie to resign from the federal ministry because of the bias in the funding allocated. She maintained that \"no project that received funding was not eligible to receive it\" and that \"no rules were broken in this program\".<ref name=\"abc-20200116\">{{cite news|last1=Norman|first1=Jane |last2=Worthington|first2=Brett|title=Bridget McKenzie facing calls to quit after auditors condemn 'biased' sports cash splash |url=https://www.abc.net.au/news/2020-01-16/sports-club-angry-at-bridget-mckenzie-government-grants/11873320|accessdate=2020-01-16|work=ABC News|location=Australia|date=2020-01-16}}</ref> The Leader of the Opposition [[Anthony Albanese]] stated that what McKenzie had done \"fails every test\" and she must be sacked.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.smh.com.au/politics/federal/it-fails-every-test-albanese-says-pm-must-sack-bridget-mckenzie-20200122-p53tlm.html|title='It fails every test': Albanese says PM must sack Bridget McKenzie|first=Rob|last=Harris|date=21 January 2020|website=The Sydney Morning Herald}}</ref>\n\nIn 1993, [[Ros Kelly]], the Labor Sports Minister in the [[Keating government]] resigned under almost identical circumstances in what came to be known as the [[Sports rorts affair|Sports Rorts affair]].\n\nMore than 70 per cent of ''[[The Australian Financial Review|Australian Financial Review]]'' readers said that McKenzie should resign over the scandal.<ref>{{cite news|author=Seo, Bo|url=https://www.afr.com/politics/federal/afr-readers-say-bridget-mckenzie-has-to-go-20200127-p53v09|title=AFR readers say Bridget McKenzie has to go\n|work=The Australian Financial Review|date=27 January 2020|accessdate=27 January 2020}}</ref>\n\n====Government response====\n\nThe government steadfastly supported McKenzie throughout the scandal. [[Prime Minister of Australia|Prime Minister]] [[Scott Morrison]]<ref>{{cite news|author=Karp, Paul|url=https://www.theguardian.com/australia-news/2020/jan/20/scott-morrison-backs-bridget-mckenzie-in-sports-grants-scandal-and-will-clarify-legal-issues|title=Scott Morrison backs Bridget McKenzie in sports grants scandal and will \u2018clarify\u2019 legal issues|work=The Guardian|date=20 January 2020|accessdate=3 February 2020}}</ref>, Michael McCormack<ref>{{cite news|author=Martin, Sarah|url=https://www.theguardian.com/australia-news/2020/jan/24/sports-grants-michael-mccormack-stands-by-bridget-mckenzie-saying-she-has-done-outstanding-job|title=Sports grants: Michael McCormack stands by Bridget McKenzie, saying she has done \u2018outstanding job\u2019|work=The Guardian|date=24 January 2020|accessdate=3 February 2020}}</ref>, [[Peter Dutton]]<ref>{{cite news|author=Tillet, Andrew|url=https://www.afr.com/politics/federal/dutton-argues-there-s-no-reason-for-bridget-mckenzie-s-scalp-20200124-p53ubr|title=Dutton argues there's no reason for Bridget McKenzie's scalp|work=The Australian Financial Review|date=24 January 2020|accessdate=2 February 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theaustralian.com.au/subscribe/news/1/?sourceCode=TAWEB_WRE170_a&dest=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.theaustralian.com.au%2Fnation%2Fpolitics%2Fgovernment-will-not-listen-to-twitter-peter-dutton-defends-bridget-mckenzie-over-sports-grants%2Fnews-story%2Fe4909b24757aa7f9be1572e871ee7e79&memtype=anonymous&mode=premium&nk=b2afb22f55a195c6b679971d08b42f8a-1580779300|title=Government will not listen to twitter: Peter Dutton defends Bridget McKenzie over sports grants|website=[[The Australian]]|date= |accessdate=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.afr.com/politics/federal/dutton-argues-there-s-no-reason-for-bridget-mckenzie-s-scalp-20200124-p53ubr|title=Dutton argues there's no reason for Bridget McKenzie's scalp|date=24 January 2020|website=Australian Financial Review}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://9now.nine.com.au/today/bridget-mckenzie-quits-government-reaction/01d930c6-0973-4585-bf45-8fedb303fb15|title=McKenzie resignation no embarrassment, insists Dutton|website=9now.nine.com.au}}</ref> and other high-profile Coalition ministers repeatedly spoke out in her defence.<ref name=\"auto\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/australia-news/2020/feb/02/sports-rort-dutton-backs-beleaguered-mckenzie-saying-ive-got-confidence-in-bridget|title=Sports rort: Dutton backs beleaguered McKenzie saying 'I've got confidence in Bridget'|author=Murphy, Katharine|date=2 February 2020|work=Guardian Australia}}</ref>\n\nFollowing the revelation that McKenzie awarded a $36,000 grant to a regional Victorian shooting club without declaring that she was a member, on 22 January 2020 Morrison referred the matter to the Commonwealth Auditor-General and the Secretary of the [[Department of the Prime Minister and Cabinet (Australia)|Department of the Prime Minister and Cabinet]] for advice in relation to the conduct of ministerial standards.<ref name=\"auto1\">{{cite news|author=Harris, Rob|url=https://www.smh.com.au/politics/federal/clip-reveals-mckenzie-gave-club-a-grant-after-joining-as-member-20200122-p53ttl.html|title=PM orders conflict of interest review of McKenzie's shooting grant|work=The Sydney Morning Herald|date=22 January 2020|accessdate=22 January 2020}}</ref> On 29 January, Morrison attempted to distance himself from the scandal after being asked questions at a National Press Club meeting. Morrison was asked why his office had approved an extra $42.5&nbsp;million for the sports grants scheme in March 2019, but did not explain.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.abc.net.au/news/2020-01-29/scott-morrison-distances-self-sports-grants-bridget-mckenzie/11909940|title=Scott Morrison distances himself from sports grants scandal plaguing his Government|first=Brett|last=Worthington|date=29 January 2020|website=ABC News}}</ref>\n\nThe report by the Secretary of the Department of Prime Minister and Cabinet determined that McKenzie had breached the ministerial code of conduct and, on 2 February, she tendered her resignation as Minister for Agriculture and Deputy Leader of her party.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.9news.com.au/national/bridget-mckenzie-resigns-over-sports-grant-scandal-australian-politics/f5c1f458-8d67-414a-8115-89f68b62767a|title=Bridget McKenzie resigns from cabinet over sports grant saga|website=www.9news.com.au}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.abc.net.au/news/2020-02-02/bridget-mckenzie-quits-over-ministerial-standards-breach/11896610|title=Bridget McKenzie quits frontbench over report she breached ministerial standards|work=[[ABC News (Australia)|ABC News]]|date=2 February 2020|accessdate = 2 February 2020|location=Australia}}</ref>\n\n==Other controversies==\n\nIn 2017, McKenzie was accused of using parliamentary travel entitlements for personal benefit, in a weekend trip to the [[Gold Coast, Queensland|Gold Coast]] in September 2014.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.theaustralian.com.au/national-affairs/barnabys-new-deputy-silent-on-weekend-trip-to-gold-coast/news-story/3a6d0f4d3c45393f6ea984a5105db709|title=Nationals new deputy silent on weekend trip to Gold Coast|date=2017-12-14|work=The Australian|access-date=2017-12-17|language=en-US}}</ref> Also questioned was a February 2017 trip to [[Sydney]] to speak at a Shooting Australia awards ceremony, which was claimed as \"electorate business\"; media reports suggested that it did not fall under the usual category of parliamentary business, and the city of Sydney is not located in the state of Victoria which Bridget represents.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.smh.com.au/federal-politics/political-news/nationals-deputy-bridget-mckenzie-charged-taxpayers-to-attend-shooting-awards-20171216-h05vqh.html|title=Nationals deputy Bridget McKenzie charged taxpayers to attend shooting awards|date=2017-12-16|work=The Sydney Morning Herald|access-date=2017-12-17|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\nMcKenzie's electorate office was in the regional city of [[Bendigo]], and she was described in media headlines{{by whom?|date=December 2017}} as \"Bendigo-based\" on a number of occasions<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bendigoadvertiser.com.au/story/5106185/bridget-mckenzie-named-new-national-party-deputy-leader/|title=Bridget McKenzie named new National Party deputy leader|date=2017-12-07|website=Bendigo Advertiser|language=en|access-date=2020-01-24}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thecourier.com.au/story/5106778/bridget-mckenzie-named-new-national-party-deputy-leader/|title=Bridget McKenzie named new National Party deputy leader|date=2017-12-07|website=The Courier|language=en|access-date=2020-01-24}}</ref>. In 2018, after maintaining the office in Bendigo as \"a National Party campaign office\" for some months following her ascension to Cabinet, McKenzie relocated her electorate office to Wodonga, some 250km away in the federal electorate of [[Division of Indi|Indi]], which led to rumours she would contest the seat,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.mailtimes.com.au/story/5832039/bridget-mckenzie-rules-out-mallee-contest-uncertain-about-indi/|title=Bridget McKenzie rules out Mallee contest, uncertain about Indi|last=Johnston|first=David|date=2019-01-01|website=The Wimmera Mail-Times|language=en|access-date=2020-01-31}}</ref> at the [[2019 Australian federal election|2019 federal election]] but eventually declined to do so. This ultimately cost taxpayers more than $500,000.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bendigoadvertiser.com.au/story/6258260/mckenzie-bills-taxpayers-530000-for-new-office/|title=McKenzie bills taxpayers $530,000 for new office|last=Johnston|first=David|date=2019-07-04|website=Bendigo Advertiser|language=en|access-date=2020-01-31}}</ref> In 2016 it was noted that her primary residence was a flat in the inner-Melbourne suburb of [[Elwood, Victoria|Elwood]], and she stayed in hotels when she visited Bendigo.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.abc.net.au/centralvic/programs/central_victoria_mornings/?site=centralvic/|title=Nationals Senator Bridget McKenzie responds to criticism she lives in the inner-city|date=2017-10-12|work=[[Australian Broadcasting Corporation]]|access-date=2017-12-18|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nMcKenzie has four children from her first marriage, which ended in divorce <ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.smh.com.au/federal-politics/political-news/meet-bridget-mckenzie-the-turnbull-government-senator-out-to-change-your-mind-about-guns-20151025-gkhubu.html|title=Meet Bridget McKenzie, the Turnbull government senator out to change your mind about guns|date=2015-10-26|work=Sydney Morning Herald|access-date=2017-11-02|language=en-US}}</ref> She was subsequently in a long-distance relationship with [[David Bennett (New Zealand politician)|David Bennett]], a member of the [[New Zealand Parliament]] and both are members of their respective countries' National Parties.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.nzherald.co.nz/nz/news/article.cfm?c_id=1&objectid=11772755|title=Trans-Tasman relations: Long-distance love for Hamilton East MP David Bennett, who confirms he is in a relationship with Australian senator|date=2016-12-24|work=NZ Herald|access-date=2017-11-02|language=en-US}}</ref><ref>[http://www.theaustralian.com.au/national-affairs/bridget-mckenzie-new-zealand-enchants-another-national/news-story/69088f1b43bc6dabf6fddfda5c5e184b Bridget McKenzie: New Zealand enchants another National], ''[[The Australian]]'', 9 December 2017. Retrieved 19 December 2017.</ref>\n\n==See also==\n{{stack|{{portal|Biography|Politics|Australia}}}}\n* [[Sports rorts affair (2020)]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.bridgetmckenzie.com.au/ Official website]\n* [https://theyvoteforyou.org.au/people/senate/victoria/bridget_mckenzie Summary of parliamentary voting for Senator Bridget McKenzie on TheyVoteForYou.org.au]\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-off}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[David Littleproud]]|as=Minister for Agriculture and Water Resources}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Minister for Agriculture (Australia)|Minister for Agriculture]]|years=2019\u20132020}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Michael McCormack (Australian politician)|Michael McCormack]]}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[John McVeigh (politician)|John McVeigh]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Minister for Regional Services, Decentralisation and Local Government]]|years=2018\u20132019}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Mark Coulton]]}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Greg Hunt]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Minister for Sport (Australia)|Minister for Sport]]|years=2017\u20132019}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Richard Colbeck]]}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Fiona Nash]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Minister for Health (Australia)#List of ministers for rural health|Minister for Rural Health]]|years=2017\u20132018}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Greg Hunt]]|as=Minister for Health}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Fiona Nash]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Minister for Communications (Australia)#List of ministers for regional communications|Minister for Regional Communications]]|years=2017\u20132018}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Mitch Fifield]]|as=Minister for Communications and the Arts}}\n{{s-ppo}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Fiona Nash]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=Deputy Leader of the [[National Party of Australia]]|years=2017\u20132020}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[David Littleproud]]}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Nigel Scullion]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=Leader of the [[National Party of Australia]] in the Senate|years=2017\u2013present}}\n{{s-inc}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{Australian Senators}}\n{{Second Turnbull Ministry}}\n{{First Morrison Ministry}}\n{{Second Morrison Ministry}}\n{{National Party of Australia}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:McKenzie, Bridget}}\n[[Category:1969 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Abbott Government]]\n[[Category:National Party of Australia members of the Parliament of Australia]]\n[[Category:Members of the Australian Senate]]\n[[Category:Members of the Australian Senate for Victoria]]\n[[Category:Women members of the Australian Senate]]\n[[Category:Deakin University alumni]]\n[[Category:Monash University faculty]]\n[[Category:Turnbull Government]]\n[[Category:Australian people of Scottish descent]]\n[[Category:People from Alexandra, Victoria]]\n[[Category:21st-century Australian politicians]]\n[[Category:21st-century Australian women politicians]]\n[[Category:Government ministers of Australia]]\n[[Category:Women government ministers of Australia]]\n[[Category:Members of the Cabinet of Australia]]\n[[Category:Morrison Government]]\n", "name_user": "BallaratNation", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bridget_McKenzie"}
{"title_page": "Swaminarayan Temple, Ahmedabad", "text_new": "<br />\n{{Infobox Mandir\n| name               = Shree Swaminarayan Mandir Kalupur Ahmedabad\n| image              = Shree Swaminarayan Sampraday, Ahmedabad.jpg\n| alt          = \n| caption            = The headquarters of the NarNarayan Dev Gadi\n| map_type        = <!-- India Gujarat -->\n| map_caption        = Location in Gujarat\n| coordinates        = \n| other_names        = \n| proper_name        = \n| country            = [[India]]\n| state              = [[Gujarat]]\n| district           = \n| location           = [[Ahmedabad]]\n| elevation_m        = \n| deity      = Narnarayan Dev, Radhakrishna Dev, Dharmadev, BhaktiMata and Harikrishna.\n| festivals= \n| architecture       = \n| temple_quantity  = \n| monument_quantity= \n| inscriptions       = \n| year_completed         = 24 February 1822\n| creator            = Shree Swaminarayan Mandir Kalupur\n| website            ={{official|http://www.swaminarayan.in}}\n|Establishment=\u0ab5\u0abf\u0a95\u0acd\u0ab0\u0aae \u0ab8\u0ab5\u0a82\u0aa4 1876}}\n\n'''Shree Swaminarayan Mandir Kalupur''' ({{lang-gu|\u0ab6\u0acd\u0ab0\u0ac0 \u0ab8\u0acd\u0ab5\u0abe\u0aae\u0abf\u0aa8\u0abe\u0ab0\u0abe\u0aaf\u0aa3 \u0aae\u0a82\u0aa6\u0abf\u0ab0, \u0a85\u0aae\u0aa6\u0abe\u0ab5\u0abe\u0aa6}}, [[Devnagari]]: \u0936\u094d\u0930\u0940 \u0938\u094d\u0935\u093e\u092e\u093f\u0930\u093e\u092f\u0923 \u092e\u0928\u094d\u0926\u093f\u0930, \u0905\u0939\u092e\u0926\u093e\u092c\u093e\u0926) is the first [[Swaminarayan temple|Temple]] of the [[Swaminarayan Sampraday]], a Hindu sect. It is located in [[Kalupur]] area of [[Ahmedabad]], the largest city in [[Gujarat]], [[India]]. It was built on the instructions of [[Swaminarayan Bhagwan|Swaminarayan]], the founder of the sect.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.ahmedabad.org.uk/religious-places/swaminarayan-temple.html | title= Ahmedabad Swaminarayan Temple}}</ref>\n\nAs per the [[Desh Vibhag Lekh|will]] of Swaminarayan, the administration of the Swaminarayan Sampraday is divided into two ''Gadi''s (seats) - [[NarNarayan Dev Gadi]] and [[LaxmiNarayan Dev Gadi]]. This Temple is the headquarters of the NarNarayan Dev Gadi.<ref name=\"isbn052165422X\">{{Cite book |author=Raymond Brady Williams |title=An Introduction to Swaminarayan Hinduism |publisher=Cambridge University Press |location= |year=2001 |url=https://archive.org/details/introductiontosw0000will |url-access=registration |quote=tejendraprasad. |isbn=978-0-521-65422-7 |oclc= |doi= |accessdate= |pages = [https://archive.org/details/introductiontosw0000will/page/36 36], 29 |ref=harv |postscript=<!--None-->}}</ref>\n\n==History==\n[[File:Swaminarayan Mandir Kalupur Ahmedabad INDIA 4.JPG|left|thumb|upright 0.6|Sculptured wooden pillar]]The land for construction of this first shrine of Swaminarayan Sampraday, was gifted by the British Imperial Government. The task of constructing this pilgrimage place was entrusted personally by Swaminarayan to Ananandand Swami. This was the first temple of the Swaminarayan Sampraday constructed as per scriptural norms with intricate carving in pure Burma-teak and constructed with sculptural art by depicting deities' episodes, auspicious symbols and religious icons representing axiomatic religion and Indian culture. The temple is believed to be a valuable cultural heritage in the socio-religious history of Gujarat and India.[[File:Swaminarayan Temple - 2.JPG|thumb|The Gateway]]'''Relations with the British Government'''\n\nA British officer, Dunlop was so impressed with activities of Swaminarayan and his followers, that on behalf of the government he gave {{convert|5000|acre|km2}} of land in [[Kalupur]] area of Ahmedabad to build this temple. When the temple was completed, the officer was so impressed by the temple that he commanded a 101 gun salute to the temple.<ref name=\"FTimes\">{{cite news|url=http://www.accessmylibrary.com/coms2/summary_0286-22598178_ITM|title=The foundations of devotion|date=2003-03-04|accessdate=2009-03-12|publisher=Asia Africa Intelligence Wire, [[Financial Times]]}}</ref>\n\nWhen the British government wanted to build a railway station in Kalupur, the temple returned part of the land, where Kalupur Railway Station stands today. The government compensated the temple by granting it {{convert|1000|acre|km2}} of land in the Narayannagar village. Although the temple had very good relations with the British government, part of the wooden carvings in the temple depict the [[1857 uprising]], which is often referred to as India's first war of Independence.<ref name=\"FTimes\" />\n\nWith its architecture based on Burma teak wood, every coloured arch and bracket is a bright different shade, something that stands out in most Swaminarayan temples.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gujarattourism.com/showpage.aspx?contentid=141&webpartid=906|title=Tourism Hubs, Ahmedabad Metropolitan, Ahmedabad, Swaminarayan Temple|publisher=Gujarattourism.com|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100103174649/http://gujarattourism.com/showpage.aspx?contentid=141&webpartid=906|archive-date=2010-01-03|url-status=dead|df=}}</ref> According to ''Anjali Desai'', author of ''India Guide Gujarat'', the temple resembles a fairytale with all its colours and opulent carvings that profusely  embellish every wooden bracket, column and arch.<ref name=\"isbn0978951700\">{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=gZRLGZNZEoEC&dq=swaminarayan+ahmedabad|title=India Guide Gujarat|author=Anjali Desai|publisher=India Guide Publications|year=2006|isbn=978-0-9789517-0-2|location=|pages=88\u201390|doi=|oclc=|ref=harv|postscript=<!--None-->|accessdate=}}</ref> The temple attracts a million people on the day after [[Diwali]].<ref name=\"FTimes\" /> The temple has a multi-story guesthouse that is air conditioned and has a fully equipped medical clinic within its compound.<ref>{{Harvnb|Williams|2001|p=ix}}</ref>\n[[File:Kalupur Swaminarayan temple Ahmedabad 1866.jpg|thumb|The temple in 1866]]\n{{Clear}}\n\n==Deities==\n[[File:Swaminarayan Temple, Ahmedabad 05.jpg|thumb|upright 0.7|Nar Narayan: installed by Swaminarayan]]\nThe primary deities of the temple are [[Nara-Narayana|NarNarayan Dev]], Radha Krishna Dev, Dharmabhaktimata and Hari Krushna Maharaj, Bal Swarup Ghanshyam Maharaj and Ranghmohal Ghanshyam Maharaj. {{Citation needed|date=October 2019}}\n\n==Architecture==\n\n===The north Gateway===\nThe central gateway of the temple is artistic. It blends local, regional and British styles of architecture and sculpture. [[Marathi language|Marathi]] and [[Rajasthan]]i folk cultures and costumes are evident on the gateway sculptors. The columns are engraved with vertical lining in [[Corinthian order]]. The top of the projected pavilions are ruminants of [[Mughal architecture]]. Statues of the women wearing frilled blouses and petticoats, carrying their kids on their waist depict the Gujarati women.<ref name=\"archi\">{{cite web | url=http://www.swaminarayan.info/mandirs/kalupur/architecture.asp | title=Architecture of Swaminarayan temple Ahmedabad | access-date=18 May 2008 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080907212126/http://www.swaminarayan.info/mandirs/kalupur/architecture.asp | archive-date=7 September 2008 | url-status=dead | df=dmy-all }}</ref> \n\n===Nar Narayan Temple===\nThis is the heart of the temple complex. The temple was constructed as per scriptural norms with intricate carving in pure Burma-teak and constructed with sculptural art by depicting deities' episodes, auspicious symbols and religious icons representing axiomatic religion and Indian culture. The temple is believed to be a valuable cultural heritage in the socio-religious history of Gujarat and India.<ref name=\"isbn0-7506-6628-5\">{{Cite book |author=Lang, Jon T. |title=Urban Design: A typology of Procedures and Products. Illustrated with over 50 Case Studies |publisher=Architectural Press |location=London |year=2005 |url=https://archive.org/details/Urban_Design_A_typology_of_Procedures_and_Products |isbn=978-0-7506-6628-2 |oclc= |doi= |accessdate= |page = [https://archive.org/details/Urban_Design_A_typology_of_Procedures_and_Products/page/n112 86] |ref=harv |postscript=<!--None-->}}</ref> The images in this temple are of Narnarayan Dev in the centre, Radhakrishna Dev on the right, Dharmadev, BhaktiMata and Harikrishna on the left of the central hall. The images were made in [[Dungarpur]] and stone came from quarries in [[Himmatnagar]] and [[Dhrangadhra]].<ref name=\"FTimes\"/> \nThe temple is also known for the attractive dresses that drape the deities. Dresses for the central Narnarayan as well as RadhaKrishna images are changed seven times a day and are never repeated.<ref name=\"isbn0978951700\"/>\n\n===Akshar Bhavan===\n[[File:Swaminarayan Temple, Ahmedabad 04.jpg|thumb|Inside the temple]]\nBesides the gods in the main temple, an idol in the form of a child, Ghanshyam Maharaj in white marble has been installed on the ground floor. Personal items of Swaminarayan have been displayed for viewing by the visitors on the ground as well as first floor. The southern side of this building is known as Tejendra Bhuvan and houses visiting pilgrims.<ref name = \"archi\"/>\n\n===Rang Mahol===\n\nAn idol of Ghanshyam Maharaj has been installed in a place called the ''Rang Mahol'' in the temple where Swaminarayan stayed during his visits to Ahmedabad. A wood carved life-size idol of Swaminarayan in standing ''sambhang'' position, was installed here fifty years after the construction of the temple. It is one of the finest specimens of wooden art sculpting in Gujarat.<ref name = \"archi\"/>\n\n===Temple for women (West)===\n\nThe Haveli (Mansion) to the west of the temple used to be the official residence of Acharya of the Narnarayan Dev Gadi. Now, the ground floor of the front side, houses the offices and the inner portion accommodates the residency of the ''Sankhya Yogi'' women (ladies who have taken celibacy vows and devoted their life to the temple). In the inner temple, the Gadiwalla (the Acharya's wife & spiritual leader of the women in the Swaminarayan Sampraday) holds religious assemblies solely for the benefit of the women. An idol of Ghanshyam Maharaj has been installed in this temple and is served by the ''Sankhya Yogi'' women devotees.<ref name = \"archi\"/>\n\nThis mansion is decorated with chandeliers, suspended lamps and large mirrors as it was supposed to be the residence of the Acharya. The brackets of the pillars in the portico as well as arches have been adorned with carvings in geometrical designs and a variety of flower and creeper motifs.<ref name = \"archi\"/>\n[[File:Swaminarayan Mandir Original Ahmedabad INDIA.JPG|thumb|left|200px|The wood sculptured haveli]]\n\n===Haveli (North)===\n\nThis three-storey mansion was constructed by Acharya Keshavprasad Maharaj in 1871.\n\nThe mansion itself rests on octagonal and square wooden pillars on which Ardh-murt relief sculpture of flowers and creepers  is engraved. Angles of wooden pillars, carved in free hand design and the shapely Bharnai, which balconies rest on. The ''Sabha mandap'', an extensive Central Hall, has been constructed on sixty pillars. There are giant size madal-shilp sculptures on twelve high pillars in the front row on which rest the portico of the first floor, capture our attention with its great artistic appeal. These sculptors include a flying Hanuman lifting the [[Devgiri]] mountain in his palm; a pot bellied Ghanesha wearing a scarlet turban in the South Indian style, miniature sculptures of several soldiers armed and dressed in Marathi turbans and costumes and herds of monkeys have been created on the religious tradition in the wooden sculptors. Some sculptors depict the 1857 uprising, with the [[Rani of Jhansi]] and other heroes narrated in carvings of these pillars.<ref name = \"archi\"/> There are a total of 12 such pillars, which depict scenes such as a Maratha warrior fighting under the Rani of Jhansi in guise of [[Durga]] the Hindu goddess, Indian leader [[Tatya Tope]] in the guise of [[Narsimha]], the lion headed form of Vishnu and that of parrots which tell the mood of the times.<ref name= \"TOIAhmedabad\">\n{{cite news\n|url=http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2009-11-26/ahmedabad/28059627_1_onkar-chauhan-walled-city-jhansi\n|title=1857 revolt etched on this temple's walls\n|newspaper= [[Times of India]]\n|accessdate=2009-12-19\n|first1=Ashish\n|last1=Vashi\n|date=2009-11-26\n}}\n</ref>\n\nSculptures of lions and elephants, birds like peacocks and parrots and perfectly engraved leaves and flowers decorate the panels. The beams, ceilings, and lower sections are adorned with engravings, artistic sculptures and free-hand designs. In this mansion, Acharya sits on the wooden seat once used by Swaminarayan in the Congregation Hall. A new residence of the saints, Vrajendraprasad Mahal and a dining hall for the devotees are also situated in this mansion.<ref name = \"archi\"/>\n\n===Haveli (East)===\nThis mansion is two storeyed. Sculptures of animal heads, flowers and creepers are carved on the wooden pillars of the portico on the ground floor. Items relating to NarNarayan Dev on the ground floor. The first and second floors house a Sanskrit and music school as well as residence for saints. The backyard hosts the residence for [[brahmchari]] (celibate) students. A well where Swaminarayan used to bathe under a dome is also part of the backyard.<ref name = \"archi\"/>\n\n==Secular area and Heritage Walk==\n[[File:Swaminarayan Temple - 4.JPG|thumb|Picture of ornate wall carvings taken during the heritage walk]]\n\nKalupur area in Ahmedabad where the temple is located in a [[Muslim]] dominated area. Communal harmony was shown during the [[2001 Gujarat earthquake]] when the Muslim neighbours cooked food and gave it to the temple authorities, who accepted it as they needed it to distribute to earthquake victims.<ref>{{cite news|title=The Gujarati spirit comes to the fore|url=http://www.hinduonnet.com/businessline/2001/02/02/stories/140260yh.htm|publisher=Business Line, [[The Hindu]]|date=2001-02-01|access-date=2009-03-12|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110704230424/http://www.hinduonnet.com/businessline/2001/02/02/stories/140260yh.htm|archive-date=2011-07-04|df=}}</ref>\n\nA Heritage Walk of Ahmedabad city was started on 19 November 1997 by the local municipal corporation in association with the Foundation for Conservation and Research of Urban Traditional Architecture (CRUTA).<ref name=\"isbn0-7506-6628-5\"/><ref name = \"modi\"/> The walk starts from this temple in the Kalupur area of the city and ends at the Jama Masjid, after touring 18 sites.<ref name = \"modi\"/> The one and a half kilometer long walk takes three hours to complete.<ref name = \"ToI1\">{{cite news|title=Pols, a huge draw with foreigners |url=http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2009-04-18/ahmedabad/28037861_1_foreign-tourists-tourist-spot-pols|newspaper=[[Times of India]]|date= 2009-04-18|accessdate=2009-06-10|first1=Luiza|last1=Bontempo}}</ref> In 1999, the temple held an exhibition of photographs relating to the culture and architecture of the city as part of the Heritage Week celebrations.<ref name=\"HW\">{{cite news|title=Heritage Week functions|url=http://www.indianexpress.com/res/web/pIe/ie/daily/19991125/ige25115.html|publisher=[[Indian Express]]|date=1999-11-25|accessdate=2009-06-20}}{{Dead link|date=June 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=no }}</ref> In 2003, Chief Minister of Gujarat, [[Narendra Modi]], chose to lead this walk along with his cabinet colleagues to spread the message of peace.<ref name = \"modi\">{{cite news|title=Modi's Heritage Walk on Monday |url=http://www.accessmylibrary.com/coms2/summary_0286-25572337_ITM|publisher=Asia Africa Intelligence Wire, [[Financial Times]]|date= 2002-05-19|accessdate=2009-03-12 | first=Sourav | last=Mukherjee}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title='Heritage walk' to wake Gujarat ministers up |url=http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2003-12-28/india/27198699_1_heritage-ministers-culture-department|newspaper=[[Times of India]]|date= 2003-12-28|accessdate=2009-03-12}}</ref>\n\n==Footnotes==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== References ==\n{{Commons category|Shri Swaminarayan Temple, Ahmedabad}}\n*{{Cite book\n |last=Williams \n |first=Raymond \n |year=2001\n |title=Introduction to Swaminarayan Hinduism\n |publisher=Cambridge University Press\n |isbn=978-0-521-65422-7\n |ref=harv\n |postscript=<!--None-->\n }}\n\n== See also ==\n\n* [[Swaminarayan]]\n* [[Swaminarayan Faith]]\n* [[Swaminarayan Temples]]\n\n{{Swaminarayan Sampraday}}\n{{coord|23.030|72.591|type:landmark_region:IN|display=title}}\n\n{{Hindu temples in Gujarat}}\n\n[[Category:Swaminarayan temples]]\n[[Category:Tourist attractions in Ahmedabad]]\n[[Category:1822 establishments in India]]\n[[Category:Hindu temples in Ahmedabad]]\n", "text_old": "Kaushal Kachhadiya{{Use Indian English|date=August 2018}}\n{{Infobox Mandir\n| name               = Shree Swaminarayan Mandir Kalupur Ahmedabad\n| image              = Shree Swaminarayan Sampraday, Ahmedabad.jpg\n| alt          = \n| caption            = The headquarters of the NarNarayan Dev Gadi\n| map_type        = <!-- India Gujarat -->\n| map_caption        = Location in Gujarat\n| coordinates        = \n| other_names        = \n| proper_name        = \n| country            = [[India]]\n| state              = [[Gujarat]]\n| district           = \n| location           = [[Ahmedabad]]\n| elevation_m        = \n| deity      = Narnarayan Dev, Radhakrishna Dev, Dharmadev, BhaktiMata and Harikrishna.\n| festivals= \n| architecture       = \n| temple_quantity  = \n| monument_quantity= \n| inscriptions       = \n| year_completed         = 24 February 1822\n| creator            = Shree Swaminarayan Mandir Kalupur\n| website            ={{official|http://www.swaminarayan.in}}\n|Establishment=\u0ab5\u0abf\u0a95\u0acd\u0ab0\u0aae \u0ab8\u0ab5\u0a82\u0aa4 1876}}\n\n'''Shree Swaminarayan Mandir Kalupur''' ({{lang-gu|\u0ab6\u0acd\u0ab0\u0ac0 \u0ab8\u0acd\u0ab5\u0abe\u0aae\u0abf\u0aa8\u0abe\u0ab0\u0abe\u0aaf\u0aa3 \u0aae\u0a82\u0aa6\u0abf\u0ab0, \u0a85\u0aae\u0aa6\u0abe\u0ab5\u0abe\u0aa6}}, [[Devnagari]]: \u0936\u094d\u0930\u0940 \u0938\u094d\u0935\u093e\u092e\u093f\u0930\u093e\u092f\u0923 \u092e\u0928\u094d\u0926\u093f\u0930, \u0905\u0939\u092e\u0926\u093e\u092c\u093e\u0926) is the first [[Swaminarayan temple|Temple]] of the [[Swaminarayan Sampraday]], a Hindu sect. It is located in [[Kalupur]] area of [[Ahmedabad]], the largest city in [[Gujarat]], [[India]]. It was built on the instructions of [[Swaminarayan Bhagwan|Swaminarayan]], the founder of the sect.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.ahmedabad.org.uk/religious-places/swaminarayan-temple.html | title= Ahmedabad Swaminarayan Temple}}</ref>\n\nAs per the [[Desh Vibhag Lekh|will]] of Swaminarayan, the administration of the Swaminarayan Sampraday is divided into two ''Gadi''s (seats) - [[NarNarayan Dev Gadi]] and [[LaxmiNarayan Dev Gadi]]. This Temple is the headquarters of the NarNarayan Dev Gadi.<ref name=\"isbn052165422X\">{{Cite book |author=Raymond Brady Williams |title=An Introduction to Swaminarayan Hinduism |publisher=Cambridge University Press |location= |year=2001 |url=https://archive.org/details/introductiontosw0000will |url-access=registration |quote=tejendraprasad. |isbn=978-0-521-65422-7 |oclc= |doi= |accessdate= |pages = [https://archive.org/details/introductiontosw0000will/page/36 36], 29 |ref=harv |postscript=<!--None-->}}</ref>\n\n==History==\n[[File:Swaminarayan Mandir Kalupur Ahmedabad INDIA 4.JPG|left|thumb|upright 0.6|Sculptured wooden pillar]]The land for construction of this first shrine of Swaminarayan Sampraday, was gifted by the British Imperial Government. The task of constructing this pilgrimage place was entrusted personally by Swaminarayan to Ananandand Swami. This was the first temple of the Swaminarayan Sampraday constructed as per scriptural norms with intricate carving in pure Burma-teak and constructed with sculptural art by depicting deities' episodes, auspicious symbols and religious icons representing axiomatic religion and Indian culture. The temple is believed to be a valuable cultural heritage in the socio-religious history of Gujarat and India.[[File:Swaminarayan Temple - 2.JPG|thumb|The Gateway]]'''Relations with the British Government'''\n\nA British officer, Dunlop was so impressed with activities of Swaminarayan and his followers, that on behalf of the government he gave {{convert|5000|acre|km2}} of land in [[Kalupur]] area of Ahmedabad to build this temple. When the temple was completed, the officer was so impressed by the temple that he commanded a 101 gun salute to the temple.<ref name=\"FTimes\">{{cite news|url=http://www.accessmylibrary.com/coms2/summary_0286-22598178_ITM|title=The foundations of devotion|date=2003-03-04|accessdate=2009-03-12|publisher=Asia Africa Intelligence Wire, [[Financial Times]]}}</ref>\n\nWhen the British government wanted to build a railway station in Kalupur, the temple returned part of the land, where Kalupur Railway Station stands today. The government compensated the temple by granting it {{convert|1000|acre|km2}} of land in the Narayannagar village. Although the temple had very good relations with the British government, part of the wooden carvings in the temple depict the [[1857 uprising]], which is often referred to as India's first war of Independence.<ref name=\"FTimes\" />\n\nWith its architecture based on Burma teak wood, every coloured arch and bracket is a bright different shade, something that stands out in most Swaminarayan temples.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gujarattourism.com/showpage.aspx?contentid=141&webpartid=906|title=Tourism Hubs, Ahmedabad Metropolitan, Ahmedabad, Swaminarayan Temple|publisher=Gujarattourism.com|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100103174649/http://gujarattourism.com/showpage.aspx?contentid=141&webpartid=906|archive-date=2010-01-03|url-status=dead|df=}}</ref> According to ''Anjali Desai'', author of ''India Guide Gujarat'', the temple resembles a fairytale with all its colours and opulent carvings that profusely  embellish every wooden bracket, column and arch.<ref name=\"isbn0978951700\">{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=gZRLGZNZEoEC&dq=swaminarayan+ahmedabad|title=India Guide Gujarat|author=Anjali Desai|publisher=India Guide Publications|year=2006|isbn=978-0-9789517-0-2|location=|pages=88\u201390|doi=|oclc=|ref=harv|postscript=<!--None-->|accessdate=}}</ref> The temple attracts a million people on the day after [[Diwali]].<ref name=\"FTimes\" /> The temple has a multi-story guesthouse that is air conditioned and has a fully equipped medical clinic within its compound.<ref>{{Harvnb|Williams|2001|p=ix}}</ref>\n[[File:Kalupur Swaminarayan temple Ahmedabad 1866.jpg|thumb|The temple in 1866]]\n{{Clear}}\n\n==Deities==\n[[File:Swaminarayan Temple, Ahmedabad 05.jpg|thumb|upright 0.7|Nar Narayan: installed by Swaminarayan]]\nThe primary deities of the temple are [[Nara-Narayana|NarNarayan Dev]], Radha Krishna Dev, Dharmabhaktimata and Hari Krushna Maharaj, Bal Swarup Ghanshyam Maharaj and Ranghmohal Ghanshyam Maharaj. {{Citation needed|date=October 2019}}\n\n==Architecture==\n\n===The north Gateway===\nThe central gateway of the temple is artistic. It blends local, regional and British styles of architecture and sculpture. [[Marathi language|Marathi]] and [[Rajasthan]]i folk cultures and costumes are evident on the gateway sculptors. The columns are engraved with vertical lining in [[Corinthian order]]. The top of the projected pavilions are ruminants of [[Mughal architecture]]. Statues of the women wearing frilled blouses and petticoats, carrying their kids on their waist depict the Gujarati women.<ref name=\"archi\">{{cite web | url=http://www.swaminarayan.info/mandirs/kalupur/architecture.asp | title=Architecture of Swaminarayan temple Ahmedabad | access-date=18 May 2008 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080907212126/http://www.swaminarayan.info/mandirs/kalupur/architecture.asp | archive-date=7 September 2008 | url-status=dead | df=dmy-all }}</ref> \n\n===Nar Narayan Temple===\nThis is the heart of the temple complex. The temple was constructed as per scriptural norms with intricate carving in pure Burma-teak and constructed with sculptural art by depicting deities' episodes, auspicious symbols and religious icons representing axiomatic religion and Indian culture. The temple is believed to be a valuable cultural heritage in the socio-religious history of Gujarat and India.<ref name=\"isbn0-7506-6628-5\">{{Cite book |author=Lang, Jon T. |title=Urban Design: A typology of Procedures and Products. Illustrated with over 50 Case Studies |publisher=Architectural Press |location=London |year=2005 |url=https://archive.org/details/Urban_Design_A_typology_of_Procedures_and_Products |isbn=978-0-7506-6628-2 |oclc= |doi= |accessdate= |page = [https://archive.org/details/Urban_Design_A_typology_of_Procedures_and_Products/page/n112 86] |ref=harv |postscript=<!--None-->}}</ref> The images in this temple are of Narnarayan Dev in the centre, Radhakrishna Dev on the right, Dharmadev, BhaktiMata and Harikrishna on the left of the central hall. The images were made in [[Dungarpur]] and stone came from quarries in [[Himmatnagar]] and [[Dhrangadhra]].<ref name=\"FTimes\"/> \nThe temple is also known for the attractive dresses that drape the deities. Dresses for the central Narnarayan as well as RadhaKrishna images are changed seven times a day and are never repeated.<ref name=\"isbn0978951700\"/>\n\n===Akshar Bhavan===\n[[File:Swaminarayan Temple, Ahmedabad 04.jpg|thumb|Inside the temple]]\nBesides the gods in the main temple, an idol in the form of a child, Ghanshyam Maharaj in white marble has been installed on the ground floor. Personal items of Swaminarayan have been displayed for viewing by the visitors on the ground as well as first floor. The southern side of this building is known as Tejendra Bhuvan and houses visiting pilgrims.<ref name = \"archi\"/>\n\n===Rang Mahol===\n\nAn idol of Ghanshyam Maharaj has been installed in a place called the ''Rang Mahol'' in the temple where Swaminarayan stayed during his visits to Ahmedabad. A wood carved life-size idol of Swaminarayan in standing ''sambhang'' position, was installed here fifty years after the construction of the temple. It is one of the finest specimens of wooden art sculpting in Gujarat.<ref name = \"archi\"/>\n\n===Temple for women (West)===\n\nThe Haveli (Mansion) to the west of the temple used to be the official residence of Acharya of the Narnarayan Dev Gadi. Now, the ground floor of the front side, houses the offices and the inner portion accommodates the residency of the ''Sankhya Yogi'' women (ladies who have taken celibacy vows and devoted their life to the temple). In the inner temple, the Gadiwalla (the Acharya's wife & spiritual leader of the women in the Swaminarayan Sampraday) holds religious assemblies solely for the benefit of the women. An idol of Ghanshyam Maharaj has been installed in this temple and is served by the ''Sankhya Yogi'' women devotees.<ref name = \"archi\"/>\n\nThis mansion is decorated with chandeliers, suspended lamps and large mirrors as it was supposed to be the residence of the Acharya. The brackets of the pillars in the portico as well as arches have been adorned with carvings in geometrical designs and a variety of flower and creeper motifs.<ref name = \"archi\"/>\n[[File:Swaminarayan Mandir Original Ahmedabad INDIA.JPG|thumb|left|200px|The wood sculptured haveli]]\n\n===Haveli (North)===\n\nThis three-storey mansion was constructed by Acharya Keshavprasad Maharaj in 1871.\n\nThe mansion itself rests on octagonal and square wooden pillars on which Ardh-murt relief sculpture of flowers and creepers  is engraved. Angles of wooden pillars, carved in free hand design and the shapely Bharnai, which balconies rest on. The ''Sabha mandap'', an extensive Central Hall, has been constructed on sixty pillars. There are giant size madal-shilp sculptures on twelve high pillars in the front row on which rest the portico of the first floor, capture our attention with its great artistic appeal. These sculptors include a flying Hanuman lifting the [[Devgiri]] mountain in his palm; a pot bellied Ghanesha wearing a scarlet turban in the South Indian style, miniature sculptures of several soldiers armed and dressed in Marathi turbans and costumes and herds of monkeys have been created on the religious tradition in the wooden sculptors. Some sculptors depict the 1857 uprising, with the [[Rani of Jhansi]] and other heroes narrated in carvings of these pillars.<ref name = \"archi\"/> There are a total of 12 such pillars, which depict scenes such as a Maratha warrior fighting under the Rani of Jhansi in guise of [[Durga]] the Hindu goddess, Indian leader [[Tatya Tope]] in the guise of [[Narsimha]], the lion headed form of Vishnu and that of parrots which tell the mood of the times.<ref name= \"TOIAhmedabad\">\n{{cite news\n|url=http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2009-11-26/ahmedabad/28059627_1_onkar-chauhan-walled-city-jhansi\n|title=1857 revolt etched on this temple's walls\n|newspaper= [[Times of India]]\n|accessdate=2009-12-19\n|first1=Ashish\n|last1=Vashi\n|date=2009-11-26\n}}\n</ref>\n\nSculptures of lions and elephants, birds like peacocks and parrots and perfectly engraved leaves and flowers decorate the panels. The beams, ceilings, and lower sections are adorned with engravings, artistic sculptures and free-hand designs. In this mansion, Acharya sits on the wooden seat once used by Swaminarayan in the Congregation Hall. A new residence of the saints, Vrajendraprasad Mahal and a dining hall for the devotees are also situated in this mansion.<ref name = \"archi\"/>\n\n===Haveli (East)===\nThis mansion is two storeyed. Sculptures of animal heads, flowers and creepers are carved on the wooden pillars of the portico on the ground floor. Items relating to NarNarayan Dev on the ground floor. The first and second floors house a Sanskrit and music school as well as residence for saints. The backyard hosts the residence for [[brahmchari]] (celibate) students. A well where Swaminarayan used to bathe under a dome is also part of the backyard.<ref name = \"archi\"/>\n\n==Secular area and Heritage Walk==\n[[File:Swaminarayan Temple - 4.JPG|thumb|Picture of ornate wall carvings taken during the heritage walk]]\n\nKalupur area in Ahmedabad where the temple is located in a [[Muslim]] dominated area. Communal harmony was shown during the [[2001 Gujarat earthquake]] when the Muslim neighbours cooked food and gave it to the temple authorities, who accepted it as they needed it to distribute to earthquake victims.<ref>{{cite news|title=The Gujarati spirit comes to the fore|url=http://www.hinduonnet.com/businessline/2001/02/02/stories/140260yh.htm|publisher=Business Line, [[The Hindu]]|date=2001-02-01|access-date=2009-03-12|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110704230424/http://www.hinduonnet.com/businessline/2001/02/02/stories/140260yh.htm|archive-date=2011-07-04|df=}}</ref>\n\nA Heritage Walk of Ahmedabad city was started on 19 November 1997 by the local municipal corporation in association with the Foundation for Conservation and Research of Urban Traditional Architecture (CRUTA).<ref name=\"isbn0-7506-6628-5\"/><ref name = \"modi\"/> The walk starts from this temple in the Kalupur area of the city and ends at the Jama Masjid, after touring 18 sites.<ref name = \"modi\"/> The one and a half kilometer long walk takes three hours to complete.<ref name = \"ToI1\">{{cite news|title=Pols, a huge draw with foreigners |url=http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2009-04-18/ahmedabad/28037861_1_foreign-tourists-tourist-spot-pols|newspaper=[[Times of India]]|date= 2009-04-18|accessdate=2009-06-10|first1=Luiza|last1=Bontempo}}</ref> In 1999, the temple held an exhibition of photographs relating to the culture and architecture of the city as part of the Heritage Week celebrations.<ref name=\"HW\">{{cite news|title=Heritage Week functions|url=http://www.indianexpress.com/res/web/pIe/ie/daily/19991125/ige25115.html|publisher=[[Indian Express]]|date=1999-11-25|accessdate=2009-06-20}}{{Dead link|date=June 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=no }}</ref> In 2003, Chief Minister of Gujarat, [[Narendra Modi]], chose to lead this walk along with his cabinet colleagues to spread the message of peace.<ref name = \"modi\">{{cite news|title=Modi's Heritage Walk on Monday |url=http://www.accessmylibrary.com/coms2/summary_0286-25572337_ITM|publisher=Asia Africa Intelligence Wire, [[Financial Times]]|date= 2002-05-19|accessdate=2009-03-12 | first=Sourav | last=Mukherjee}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title='Heritage walk' to wake Gujarat ministers up |url=http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2003-12-28/india/27198699_1_heritage-ministers-culture-department|newspaper=[[Times of India]]|date= 2003-12-28|accessdate=2009-03-12}}</ref>\n\n==Footnotes==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== References ==\n{{Commons category|Shri Swaminarayan Temple, Ahmedabad}}\n*{{Cite book\n |last=Williams \n |first=Raymond \n |year=2001\n |title=Introduction to Swaminarayan Hinduism\n |publisher=Cambridge University Press\n |isbn=978-0-521-65422-7\n |ref=harv\n |postscript=<!--None-->\n }}\n\n== See also ==\n\n* [[Swaminarayan]]\n* [[Swaminarayan Faith]]\n* [[Swaminarayan Temples]]\n\n{{Swaminarayan Sampraday}}\n{{coord|23.030|72.591|type:landmark_region:IN|display=title}}\n\n{{Hindu temples in Gujarat}}\n\n[[Category:Swaminarayan temples]]\n[[Category:Tourist attractions in Ahmedabad]]\n[[Category:1822 establishments in India]]\n[[Category:Hindu temples in Ahmedabad]]\n", "name_user": "KACHHADIYA kaushal", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Swaminarayan_Temple,_Ahmedabad"}
{"title_page": "Straight Outta Compton", "text_new": "{{About|the N.W.A album|the song|Straight Outta Compton (song)|the film|Straight Outta Compton (film)|other uses|Straight Outta Compton (disambiguation)}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=September 2012}}\n{{Infobox album\n| name       = Straight Outta Compton\n| type       = studio\n| artist     = [[N.W.A]]\n| cover      = StraightOuttaComptonN.W.A..jpg\n| alt        = The members of N.W.A. look down to the camera and  Eazy-E points a gun to it\n| released   = {{Start date|1988|8|8|mf=yes}}<ref name=\"rollingstone-kory-grow\">{{cite web|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-news/n-w-as-straight-outta-compton-12-things-you-didnt-know-707207/|title=N.W.A's 'Straight Outta Compton': 12 Things You Didn't Know|website=rollingstone.com|publisher=Rolling Stone, LLC|author=Kory Grow|date=August 8, 2018|access-date=June 9, 2019}}</ref>\n| recorded   = 1987&ndash;88\n| venue      =\n| studio     = Audio Achievements, [[Torrance, California]]\n| genre      = {{hlist|[[West Coast hip hop]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.allmusic.com/album/straight-outta-compton-mw0000653426|title=Straight Outta Compton \u2013 N.W.A \u2013 Songs, Reviews, Credits \u2013 AllMusic|website=AllMusic}}</ref>|[[gangsta rap]]|[[hardcore hip hop]]}}\n| length     = 60:16\n| label      = {{hlist|[[Ruthless Records|Ruthless]]|[[Priority Records|Priority]]}}\n| producer   = {{hlist|[[Dr. Dre]]|[[DJ Yella]]|[[Eazy-E]] {{small|([[Executive producer#Music|exec.]])}}}}\n| prev_title = [[N.W.A. and the Posse]]\n| prev_year  = 1987\n| next_title = [[100 Miles and Runnin']]\n| next_year  = 1990\n| misc       = {{Singles\n | name        = Straight Outta Compton\n | type        = studio\n | single1     = [[Straight Outta Compton (song)|Straight Outta Compton]]\n | single1date = July 10, 1988\n | single2     = [[Gangsta Gangsta (N.W.A song)|Gangsta Gangsta]]\n | single2date = September 5, 1988\n | single3     = [[Express Yourself (N.W.A song)|Express Yourself]]\n | single3date = March 27, 1989\n}}\n}}\n\n'''''Straight Outta Compton''''', a pioneering rap album, is the first studio album by the American rap group [[N.W.A]], formed in the Los Angeles area's [[City of Compton]]. Released on August 8, 1988,<ref  name=\"rollingstone-kory-grow\" /> by [[Ruthless Records]], cofounded by N.W.A member [[Eazy-E]], the album was [[Record producer|produced]] by N.W.A members [[Dr. Dre]] and [[DJ Yella]]. (Incidentally, this is N.W.A's only ''studio'' album with producer [[Arabian Prince]], gone since late 1988, and with rapper [[Ice Cube]], gone since late 1989, although both figure into the group's 1987 ''compilation'' album, [[N.W.A. and the Posse|''N.W.A and the Posse'']]\u2014which, if to little notice, had debuted the group\u2014whereas [[MC Ren]], alike Eazy, Dre, and Yella, is on both of N.W.A's studio albums, this and May 1991's ''[[Niggaz4Life]]''.) \n\n''Straight Outta Compton'' peaked at number 37 on [[Billboard 200|''Billboard''<nowiki/>'s Top LPs]] chart and at the 9th spot on [[Top R&B/Hip-Hop Albums|''Billboard''<nowiki/>'s Top Soul LPs]].<ref name=\"AMG-Sales\" /> \"[[Fuck tha Police]]\", the track most controversial, spurred alarm that N.W.A was the \"World's Most Dangerous Group\".<ref name=\":0\" /> Yet at this album's success, with much media attention and with [[platinum sales]] despite scarce radio play beyond the Los Angeles area,<ref name=\":2\">David Diallo, ch 10 \"From electro-rap to G-funk: A social history of rap music in Los Angeles and Compton, California\", in Mickey Hess, ed., ''Hip Hop in America: A Regional Guide'', Volume 1: ''East Coast and West Coast'' (Santa Barbara, CA: Greenwood Press, 2010), [https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=XkCncJ7j744C&q=Eazy-E pp 234\u2013238].</ref> other rappers increasingly followed suit with violent and lewd lyrics,<ref>{{cite book|last1=Chang|first1=Jeff|url=https://books.google.com/?id=4aofRcBRvMgC&pg=PA327#v=onepage&q&f=false|title=Can't Stop, Won't Stop: A History of the Hip-Hop Generation|date=2005-01-02|publisher=Macmillan Publishers|isbn=978-0-312-30143-9|pages=327\u2013328|accessdate=1 April 2015}}</ref> although N.W.A itself disbanded in 1991 with Dr. Dre's departure. As the 1990s closed, N.W.A's splintering and ripple effects, via the solo careers of N.W.A alumni Ice Cube and especially Dr. Dre, gangsta rap had transformed rap, R&B, and pop music while reshaping pop culture.<ref name=\"Huey\" />\n\n[[Remaster]]<nowiki/>ed, the album's reissue arrived on September 24, 2002, with four bonus tracks. For the 20th anniversary, an extended version arrived on December 4, 2007.<ref>Omar Burgess (October 10, 2007). [http://www.hiphopdx.com/index/news/id.5805/title.hhdx-news-bits-n-w-a-and-eazy-e HHDX News Bits: NWA And Eazy-E]. HipHopDX. Retrieved October 10, 2007.</ref> And in November 2015, months after its reissue on red cassettes of [[limited edition]],<ref>[[Universal Music Group]] had announced that on April 15, it would reissue the album, in Universal's series ''Respect The Classics'' series, on a limited-edition red cassettes [Pietro Fililpponi, [https://web.archive.org/web/20150924023527/http://www.gotham-news.com/node/21222 \"Universal announces more N.W.A re-releases, 'Straight Outta Compton' cassette tape, Friday 20th anniversary vinyl\"], ''Gotham News'' website, Gotham News LLC, 2 Apr 2015].</ref> the album reached [[RIAA certification|triple-platinum sales]]. In 2003, ''[[Rolling Stone]]'' magazine, ranking the [[Rolling Stone's 500 Greatest Albums of All Time|500 Greatest Albums of All Time]], placed this 1988 album of N.W.A at the 144th spot\u2014incidentally, then fifth among rap albums\u2014an overall ranking perpetuated in the list's 2012 update.<ref>{{cite web| url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-lists/500-greatest-albums-of-all-time-156826/n-w-a-straight-outta-compton-3-164258/|year=2012| title=500 Greatest Albums of All Time | work=[[Rolling Stone]]| accessdate= September 18, 2019}}</ref> In 2016, ''Straight Outta Compton'' became the first rap album inducted into the [[Grammy Hall of Fame]].<ref name=\":1\" /> And the United States Library of Congress, in 2017, enshrined ''Straight Outta Compton'', for its being \"culturally, historically, or artistically significant\", in the [[National Recording Registry]].<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.loc.gov/item/prn-17-029/ | title=National Recording Registry Picks Are \"Over the Rainbow\" | work=Library of Congress | date=March 29, 2016 | accessdate=March 29, 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Background==\nThe album attained triple-platinum sales, initially reaching platinum despite scarce radio play beyond the Los Angeles area,<ref name=\"AMG-Bio\">Stephen Thomas Erlewine, [https://www.allmusic.com/artist/nwa-mn0000314793/biography \"N.W.A: Biography\"], ''AllMusic.com'',  Netaktion LLC, visited 25 Apr 2020.</ref> where Greg Mack, on [[KDAY]] radio, granted N.W.A effectively direct access.<ref name=\":2\" />\n\nAs the hip hop community worldwide received the album with a high note, the members of [[N.W.A]] became the top stars for the emerging new era of [[gangsta rap]] while popularizing the lyrics of [[Ice Cube]] and [[MC Ren]]. The album also helped to spawn many young [[Rapping|MC]]s and gangsta hip hop groups from areas such as [[Compton, California]], and [[South Central Los Angeles]], as many thought they had the same story to tell and the ability to pursue the career track that N.W.A had taken,<ref name=\"Huey\"/> hence the formation of groups such as [[Compton's Most Wanted]].<ref name=mp3.com>[http://www.mp3.com/albums/22123/summary.html Compton's Most Wanted] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071213013615/http://www.mp3.com/albums/22123/summary.html |date=December 13, 2007 }}. MP3.com. Retrieved September 30, 2007.</ref>\n\nBecause of the recurring violent and sexual lyrics and profanity, often specifically directed at governmental organizations such as the [[Los Angeles Police Department|LAPD]], N.W.A always enjoyed a particular reputation with [[U.S. Senators]] and the [[Federal Bureau of Investigation]] (FBI), as noted in the LP's published notes. This situation persisted over the years with the group's visible head, [[Eazy-E]]. One of the reasons for this was \"[[Fuck tha Police]]\", the highly controversial track from the album that resulted in the FBI and the [[U.S. Secret Service]] sending a letter to Ruthless Records informing the label of their displeasure with the song's message, and that N.W.A was banned from performing at several venues.<ref name=AMG-Bio/><ref name=Eazy-e/> The FBI letter only helped further popularize the album and N.W.A.; In the group's 1990 song \"[[100 Miles and Runnin' (song)|100 Miles and Runnin']]\", while the music video shows the crew running from the police, Dr. Dre raps \"and now the FBI is all over my dick!\" as a response to the FBI's warnings.<ref>{{cite web|title=NWA \u2013 100 Miles And Running Lyrics|url=http://www.metrolyrics.com/100-miles-and-running-lyrics-nwa.html|website=MetroLyrics|accessdate=1 April 2015}}</ref> Also, in his 1990 song \"AmeriKKKa's Most Wanted\", Ice Cube mocks the FBI with the line \"With a pay-off, cop gotta lay off, FBI on my dick, stay off\".<ref>{{cite web|title=Ice Cube \u2013 AmeriKKKa's Most Wanted Lyrics|url=http://www.metrolyrics.com/amerikkkas-most-wanted-lyrics-ice-cube.html|website=MetroLyrics|accessdate=1 April 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Music==\n\n===Lyrics===\n{{Listen\n |filename     = N.W.A - Fuck Tha Police.ogg\n |title        = \"Fuck tha Police\"\n |description  = One of N.W.A's most well-known and controversial songs\n |filename2    = N.W.A - Straight Outta Compton.ogg\n |title2       = \"Straight Outta Compton\"\n |description2 = The lead single and title track. Features aggressive lyricism\n |filename3    = N.W.A - Gangsta Gangsta.ogg\n |title3       = \"Gangsta Gangsta\"\n |description3 = The second single from ''Straight Outta Compton''\n}}\n\nThe lyrics on the album were written by [[Ice Cube]], [[MC Ren]], and [[The D.O.C]]. Some critics of the album expressed their view that the record glamorized [[Black-on-Black crime]], but others stated that the group was simply showing the reality of living in the areas of [[Compton, California]], and [[South Central Los Angeles]]. Steve Huey in a retrospective review for [[AllMusic]] feels that the lyrics are more about \"raising hell\" than social criticism, but also feels the album is \"refreshingly uncalculated\" due to its humor\u2014something he feels is rare in hardcore rap.<ref name=\"Huey\"/>\n\nMany critics feel that the album's lyrics glamorize gang violence. ''[[The Washington Post]]'' writer [[David Mills (writer)|David Mills]] wrote: \"The hard-core street rappers defend their violent lyrics as a reflection of 'reality'. But for all the gunshots they mix into their music, rappers rarely try to dramatize that reality \u2014 a young man flat on the ground, a knot of lead in his chest, pleading as death slowly takes him in. It's easier for them to imagine themselves pulling the trigger\". However, ''Wichita Eagle-Beacon'' editor Bud Norman noted that \"They [[N.W.A]] don't make it sound like much fun&nbsp;... They describe it with the same nonjudgmental resignation that a Kansan might use about a tornado.\"<ref name=eNotes/>\n\n===Production===\nThe production on the album was generally seen as top-quality for the time,<ref name=\"Butler\">Butler, Nick. [http://www.sputnikmusic.com/album.php?albumid=1433 Review: ''Straight Outta Compton'']. [[Sputnikmusic]]. Retrieved on July 22, 2009.</ref> with [[Dr. Dre]]'s production performing well with the [[drum machine]] beats and [[DJ Yella]]'s turntable scratches. Some critics find it somewhat sparse and low-budget given the significance of the album and compared with other producers of the time, such as [[Marley Marl]].<ref name=\"Huey\"/>\n\n===Content===\nThe album's most controversial track, \"[[Fuck tha Police]]\", was partly responsible for the fame of N.W.A as the \"World's Most Dangerous Group\",<ref name=\":0\">McDermott, Terry (April 14, 2002). [http://www.daveyd.com/nwalatimespt1.html \"NWA:Straight Outta Compton pt\"]. ''[[Los Angeles Times]]''. Reprinted at Hip Hop News. Retrieved August 15, 2015.</ref> and it did not appear on the censored version of the album.<ref>[http://www.artistdirect.com/nad/store/artist/album/0,,1742756,00.html \"Straight Outta Compton Clean Version\"]. Artist Direct. Retrieved August 15, 2015.</ref> The song \"[[Gangsta Gangsta (N.W.A. song)|Gangsta Gangsta]]\" talks about the danger and violence in [[South Los Angeles|South Central]] and [[Compton, California|Compton]]. \"[[Express Yourself (N.W.A. song)|Express Yourself]]\" speaks of the ideas of free expression and the constraints placed on performers by radio censorship. Every N.W.A member except [[DJ Yella]] recorded a solo song. MC Ren made his solo performance on two songs; \"If It Ain't Ruff\" and \"Quiet on tha Set\". [[Dr. Dre]], who mostly produced rather than performed, did a solo effort on the single \"Express Yourself\". Ice Cube performed on \"I Ain't tha 1\".  [[Eazy-E]]'s only solo recording was a remix of the song \"8 Ball\", which appeared on N.W.A's previous album ''[[N.W.A. and the Posse]]''. The only guests on the album were Ruthless Records ghostwriter [[the D.O.C.]], who appeared on \"Parental Discretion Iz Advised\", [[rapping|rhyming]] the intro, and founding N.W.A member [[Arabian Prince]], who contributed minor vocals on \"Something 2 Dance 2\".\n\nSix tracks from the album were released on ''[[Greatest Hits (N.W.A)|N.W.A's Greatest Hits]]'': \"[[Gangsta Gangsta (N.W.A. song)|Gangsta Gangsta]]\", \"[[Fuck tha Police]]\", \"[[Straight Outta Compton (song)|Straight Outta Compton]]\" (extended mix), \"If It Ain't Ruff\", \"I Ain't tha 1\" and \"[[Express Yourself (N.W.A song)|Express Yourself]]\".\n\n==Critical reception==\n{{Album ratings\n| rev1 = [[AllMusic]]\n| rev1Score = {{Rating|5|5}}<ref name=\"Huey\">{{cite web|last=Huey|first=Steve|url=https://www.allmusic.com/album/straight-outta-compton-mw0000653426|title=Straight Outta Compton \u2013 N.W.A|website=[[AllMusic]]|accessdate=September 1, 2012}}</ref>\n| rev2 = ''[[Blender (magazine)|Blender]]''\n| rev2Score = {{Rating|5|5}}<ref name=\"Mao\">{{cite journal|author=Chairman Mao|url=http://www.blender.com/guide/reissue/50619/straight-outta-comptonefil4zaggin.html|title=N.W.A: Straight Outta Compton/Efil4Zaggin|journal=[[Blender (magazine)|Blender]]|location=New York|accessdate=August 19, 2015|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100419175800/http://www.blender.com/guide/reissue/50619/straight-outta-comptonefil4zaggin.html|archivedate=April 19, 2010}}</ref>\n| rev3 = ''[[Chicago Tribune]]''\n| rev3Score = {{Rating|3.5|4}}<ref name=\"Kot\">{{cite news|last=Kot|first=Greg|authorlink=Greg Kot|url=http://articles.chicagotribune.com/1989-07-13/features/8902170208_1_star-public-enemy-rap|title=N.W.A.: Straight Outta Compton (Ruthless/Priority)|newspaper=[[Chicago Tribune]]|date=July 13, 1989|accessdate=May 6, 2016}}</ref>\n| rev4 = ''[[Encyclopedia of Popular Music]]''\n| rev4Score = {{Rating|5|5}}<ref>{{cite book|last=Larkin|first=Colin|authorlink=Colin Larkin (writer)|year=2011|page=1643|title=The Encyclopedia of Popular Music|publisher=[[Omnibus Press]]|isbn=978-0-85712-595-8|edition=5th concise|title-link=Encyclopedia of Popular Music}}</ref>\n| rev5 = ''[[Los Angeles Times]]''\n| rev5Score = {{Rating|3.5|4}}<ref>{{cite news|last=Hunt|first=Dennis|url=https://articles.latimes.com/1989-03-19/entertainment/ca-174_1_ghetto-life|title=N.W.A. 'Straight Outta Compton.' Priority/Ruthless|newspaper=[[Los Angeles Times]]|date=March 19, 1989|accessdate=May 6, 2016}}</ref>\n| rev6 = ''[[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]]''\n| rev6Score = 9.7/10<ref name=\"Linhardt\">{{cite web|last=Linhardt|first=Alex|url=https://pitchfork.com/reviews/albums/11791-straight-outta-compton-efil4zaggin/|title=N.W.A: Straight Outta Compton / Efil4zaggin|work=[[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]]|date=October 2, 2003|accessdate=July 22, 2009}}</ref>\n| rev7 = ''[[Q (magazine)|Q]]''\n| rev7Score = {{Rating|2|5}}<ref name=\"Dick\">{{cite journal|last=Dick|first=Charlie|title=N.W.A: Straight Outta Compton|journal=[[Q (magazine)|Q]]|location=London|issue=38|date=November 1989}}</ref>\n| rev8 = ''[[Rolling Stone]]''\n| rev8Score = {{Rating|5|5}}<ref name=\"Caramanica\">{{cite journal|last=Caramanica|first=Jon|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/reviews/album/128098/review/6211658/straightouttacompton|title=Straight Outta Compton : N.W.A.|journal=[[Rolling Stone]]|location=New York|issue=907|date=October 17, 2002|accessdate=July 22, 2009|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071106071456/http://www.rollingstone.com/reviews/album/128098/review/6211658/straightouttacompton|archivedate=November 6, 2007}}</ref>\n| rev9 = ''[[Uncut (magazine)|Uncut]]''\n| rev9Score = {{Rating|5|5}}<ref>{{cite journal|title=N.W.A: Straight Outta Compton|journal=[[Uncut (magazine)|Uncut]]|location=London|issue=66|date=November 2002|page=141}}</ref>\n| rev10 = ''[[The Village Voice]]''\n| rev10Score = B<ref>{{cite news|last=Christgau|first=Robert|authorlink=Robert Christgau|url=http://www.robertchristgau.com/xg/cg/cgv489-89.php|title=Consumer Guide|newspaper=[[The Village Voice]]|location=New York|date=April 25, 1989|accessdate=May 6, 2016}}</ref>\n}}\nIn a contemporary review for the ''[[Chicago Tribune]]'', [[Greg Kot]] found N.W.A.'s music \"fuller and funkier\" than [[Public Enemy (group)|Public Enemy]]'s and their lyrics just as \"unforgiving\".<ref name=\"Kot\"/> The ''[[Orange County Register]]'' noted the explicit language on the album, noting that it made fellow rapper [[Ice-T]] \"look like a Cub Scout\".<ref name=\"ocr-review\">{{cite news|newspaper=[[Orange County Register]]|title=Fine Young Cannibals dish out an underdone album|last1=Darling|first1=Cary|date=March 3, 1989}}</ref>\nThe review concluded that the album was \"curiously uninvolving\" and that it \"lacks the insight and passion that put the best work by the likes of [[Boogie Down Productions]], [[Ice-T]] and [[Public Enemy (band)|Public Enemy]] so far ahead of the field\".<ref name=\"ocr-review\" /> The ''[[Richmond Times-Dispatch]]''{{'}}s Mark Holmberg described the album as \"a preacher-provoking, mother-maddening, reality-stinks diatribe that wallows in gangs, doping, drive-by shootings, brutal sexism, cop slamming and racism\".<ref name=eNotes>Ed. Michael L. LaBlanc. (December 4, 2006). [http://www.enotes.com/contemporary-musicians/n-w-biography \"N.W.A.\" Contemporary Musicians]. eNotes. Retrieved October 10, 2007</ref> ''[[Newsweek]]'' noted that ''Straight Outta Compton'' \"introduced some of the most grotesquely exciting music ever made\", and added that \"Hinting at gang roots, and selling themselves on those hints, they project a gangster mystique that pays no attention where criminality begins and marketing lets off\".<ref name=eNotes/>\n\nFollowing its 2002 re-release, Jon Caramanica of ''[[Rolling Stone]]'' magazine cited ''Straight Outta Compton'' as one of hip-hop's \"most crucial albums\", calling it a \"bombastic, cacophonous car ride through Los Angeles' burnt-out and ignored hoods.\"<ref name=\"Caramanica\"/>\n\n\"The lyrics on this record are unrelenting in their unpleasantness,\" lamented Peter Clarke in ''[[Hi-Fi News & Record Review]]'', awarding the album a rock-bottom \"D:4\" rating. \"The cumulative effect is like listening to an endless fight next door. The music on this record is without a hint of dynamics or melody.\"<ref>''[[Hi-Fi News & Record Review]]'', December 1989</ref> \"In the wake of [[Public Enemy (band)|Public Enemy]] and [[KRS-One]], it is amazing that something this lightweight could cause such a stir,\" stated Charlie Dick in a two-star review for ''[[Q (magazine)|Q]]''. \"The all-mouth-and-trousers content is backed up by likable [[drum machine]] twittering, minimal instrumentation and duffish production&nbsp;... This regressive nonsense will be passed off as social commentary by thrill-seekers all across the free world.\"<ref name=\"Dick\"/>\n\n===Accolades===\n\"It's definitely the best rap record I've ever heard,\" remarked [[Sin\u00e9ad O'Connor]]. \"Of course, I can see why people might be offended by the lyrics. But as a human being and not as a public figure, I'm not offended at all. I realise from reading interviews with people like Ice Cube, when they explain that they're not talking about women in general but about particular women they know, it makes a lot of sense. I think the sound of the record is brilliant. I really like hardcore hip-hop and reggae stuff, so it's right up my flight of stairs.\"<ref>''[[Rolling Stone]]'', 15 November 1990</ref>\n\n\"Rappers haven't always referred to themselves as 'niggers' on record,\" remarked ''[[Hip Hop Connection]]'', placing it at No.3 on their countdown of rap's best albums. \"It came as something of a shock then that here were five politically astute black men calling themselves niggers and their women bitches at a time when Afrocentric rap was the current vogue&nbsp;... ''Straight Outta Compton'' sounded so exciting, insignificant details such as realism and integrity could be overlooked.\"<ref>''[[Hip Hop Connection]]'', July 1994</ref>\n\nIn 2003, the TV network [[VH1]] named ''Straight Outta Compton'' the 62nd greatest album of all time.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dailycelebrations.com/vh1_albums.htm |title= VH1 List of 100 Best Rock Albums |publisher=dailycelebrations.com |date= |accessdate=2016-02-16}}</ref>\n\nIt was ranked ten in ''[[Spin (magazine)|Spin]]'' magazine's \"100 Greatest Albums, 1985\u20132005\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rocklistmusic.co.uk/spin100.html |title=Spin 20th Anniversary Special, July 2005 |publisher=rocklistmusic.co.uk |date=2005-07-01 |accessdate=2016-02-16}}</ref>\n\nIn 1998, the album was selected as #68 of The Source's 100 Best Rap Albums.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://rateyourmusic.com/list/Tempetz/the_sources_top_100_rap_albums_of_all_time/|title=The Source's Top 100 Rap Albums of All Time |publisher=rateyourmusic.com |date=|accessdate=2016-02-16}}</ref>\n\nIt is the group's only album on ''Rolling Stone''{{'}}s list of the [[Rolling Stone's 500 Greatest Albums of All Time|500 Greatest Albums of All Time]] (ranked #144), and the first hip hop album ever to get a 5-star rating from them in their initial review. When comedian [[Chris Rock]] wrote an article for the magazine about the 25 Greatest Hip Hop Albums of all time in 2005, ''Straight Outta Compton'' was number one on his list.<ref>{{cite web| first= Chris | last=Rock| authorlink= Chris Rock| url= http://rateyourmusic.com/list/tha_flu/chris_rocks_top_25_hip_hop_albums |title= Chris Rock's Top 25 Hip Hop Albums| website= RateYourMusic.com| accessdate= October 6, 2007}}</ref>\n\nThe album is ranked the 112th best of all time by Acclaimedmusic.net.<ref>[http://www.acclaimedmusic.net Acclaimed Music website]. [[Acclaimed Music]]. Accessed October 6, 2007.</ref>\n\nIn 2006, the album was listed in the book ''[[1001 Albums You Must Hear Before You Die]]''.<ref name=1001Albums>[http://www.rocklistmusic.co.uk/steveparker/1001albums.htm 1001 Albums You Must Hear Before You Die] Rocklistmusic. Retrieved October 25, 2007</ref> The same year, ''[[Time (magazine)|Time]]'' magazine ranked it as one of the 100 greatest albums of all time.<ref name=TIME>[http://www.time.com/time/2006/100albums/index.html The All-TIME 100 Albums] ''TIME''. Accessed January 4, 2008</ref>\n\n''[[Q (magazine)|Q]]'' magazine voted it one of the 'Top 50 Titles of 1989'. ''[[Alternative Press (music magazine)|Alternative Press]]'' ranked it #45 in AP's list of the 'Top 99 of '85\u2013'95'.<ref name= AltPress>{{cite news| url= | work= [[Alternative Press (music magazine)|Alternative Press]]| date= July 1995| page= 88| title= Top 99 of '85\u2013'95| publisher= | first= | last=}}</ref> [[Vibe (magazine)|''Vibe'']] included it in Vibe's 100 Essential Albums of the 20th Century.<ref name= Vibe-Ess>{{cite news| work= [[Vibe (magazine)|Vibe]] | url= | date= December 1999| page= 164 | title= 100 Essential Albums of the 20th Century| publisher= | first= | last= }}</ref> In 2004, ''DigitaArts'' included the album's cover in its list of the 25 Best Albums Covers.<ref>Staff (June 14, 2004). [http://www.digitalartsonline.co.uk/features/index.cfm?featureid=1082 The 25 Best Album Covers]. ''DigitalArts''. Retrieved on September 27, 2010.</ref> In 2012, ''[[Slant Magazine|Slant]]'' listed the album at #18 on its list of \"Best Albums of the 1980s\" saying \"The juxtaposition of midtempo, Cali-languid grooves and violent wordplay positioned Straight Outta Compton as the sound of the West Coast firing on New York's Fort Sumpter in what would become '90s culture's biggest Uncivil War.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.slantmagazine.com/music/feature/best-albums-of-the-1980s/308/page_9|title=The 100 Best Albums of the 1980s \u2013 Feature \u2013 Slant Magazine|work=Slant Magazine|accessdate=August 14, 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn November 2016, the album was inducted into the [[Grammy Hall of Fame]], becoming the first hip-hop album to receive this honor.<ref name=\":1\">{{cite web|url= http://www.grammy.com/news/grammy-hall-of-fame-adds-25-recordings| title= Grammy Hall of Fame Adds 25 Recordings| website= grammy.com| publisher= [[The Recording Academy]]| year= 2016| url-status= unfit| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20161204101933/http://www.grammy.com/news/grammy-hall-of-fame-adds-25-recordings| archivedate= 2016-12-04| |accessdate= 2020-03-11}}</ref>\n\n==Commercial performance==\nThe album first appeared on music charts in 1989, peaking on the US [[Billboard 200|''Billboard'' Top LPs]] chart at number 37, and peaking on ''[[Billboard charts|Billboard]]''{{'}}s [[Top R&B/Hip-Hop Albums|Top Soul LPs]] at number 9.<ref name=AMG-Sales>[{{Allmusic|class=artist|id=p77|pure_url=yes}} N.W.A \u2013 Discography, Charts and Awards]. Allmusic. Accessed October 9, 2007.</ref> It re-entered the charts in 2003, peaking on the UK Albums Top 75 at number 35, and on the Ireland Albums Top 75 at number 20.<ref name=acharts>[http://acharts.us/album/16362 N.W.A \u2013 Straight Outta Compton Chart Positions]. aCharts. Accessed October 9, 2007.</ref>\n\nThe album has sold over three million copies<ref name=Eazy-e>[http://www.eazy-e.com/eazy_e-timeline.php Eazy-E Timeline]. Eazy-E.com. Accessed October 4, 2007</ref><ref name=LA-Times>[http://www.daveyd.com/nwalatimespt1.html Straight Outta Compton article]. ''Los Angeles Times''. Accessed October 4, 2007</ref> and was certified triple platinum on November 11, 2015.<ref>[https://www.riaa.com/goldandplatinumdata.php?resultpage=1&table=SEARCH_RESULTS&action=&title=Straight%20Outta%20Compton&artist=N.W.A&format=&debutLP=&category=&sex=&releaseDate=&requestNo=&type=&level=&label=&company=&certificationDate=&awardDescription=&catalogNo=&aSex=&rec_id=&charField=&gold=&platinum=&multiPlat=&level2=&certDate=&album=&id=&after=&before=&startMonth=1&endMonth=1&startYear=1958&endYear=2007&sort=Artist&perPage=25 RIAA Searchable database \u2013 ''Straight Outta Compton''] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151017045413/http://www.riaa.com/goldandplatinumdata.php?resultpage=1&table=SEARCH_RESULTS&action=&title=Straight%20Outta%20Compton&artist=N.W.A&format=&debutLP=&category=&sex=&releaseDate=&requestNo=&type=&level=&label=&company=&certificationDate=&awardDescription=&catalogNo=&aSex=&rec_id=&charField=&gold=&platinum=&multiPlat=&level2=&certDate=&album=&id=&after=&before=&startMonth=1&endMonth=1&startYear=1958&endYear=2007&sort=Artist&perPage=25 |date=October 17, 2015 }}. RIAA. Retrieved October 10, 2007.</ref> It was [[N.W.A]]'s best-selling album, as their debut, ''[[N.W.A and the Posse]]'', was certified gold by the RIAA. Their final album, ''[[Niggaz4Life]]'', was certified double platinum by the RIAA. According to [[Priority Records]]' calculations, 80% of sales were in the suburbs, beyond the boundaries of black neighborhoods.<ref name=LA-Times /> A week before release of the 2015 biopic film ''[[Straight Outta Compton (film)|Straight Outta Compton]]'', the album re-entered the Billboard 200 at number&nbsp;173. It later rose to number&nbsp;30 due to the popularity of the film, surpassing its original peak position back in 1989 when it peaked at number&nbsp;37.<ref name=\"hiphopdx.com\">{{cite web|url=http://hiphopdx.com/news/id.35109/title.hip-hop-album-sales-dr-dre-kendrick-lamar-n-w-a|title=Hip Hop Album Sales: Dr. Dre, Kendrick Lamar & N.W.A|author=HipHopDX|date=August 17, 2015|work=HipHopDX}}</ref> The album peaked at number 4 following the opening weekend of the movie.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/chart-beat/6671228/luke-bryan-kill-the-lights-billboard-200-second-week|title=Luke Bryan's 'Kill the Lights' Spends Second Week at No. 1 on Billboard 200|work=Billboard}}</ref> On November 11, 2015, the album was certified triple platinum by the RIAA for exceeding sales of 3 million copies in the US.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.riaa.com/goldandplatinumdata.php?content_selector=gold-platinum-searchable-database# |title=Gold & Platinum |work=RIAA |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130905082250/http://riaa.com/goldandplatinumdata.php?content_selector=gold-platinum-searchable-database |archivedate=September 5, 2013 }}</ref>\n\n==In popular culture==\n{{See also|1=Special:PrefixIndex/Straight Outta}}\nThe album cover and title has been parodied by American cartoonist [[Bill Holbrook]] for his ''[[Kevin and Kell]]'' 2004 collection as \"Straight Outta Computers\";<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.paperbackswap.com/Straight-Outta-Computers-Bill-Holbrook/book/1929462875/|title=Straight Outta Computers|work=PaperBackSwap.com|accessdate=August 14, 2015}}</ref> [[Wales|Welsh]] novelty hip hop group [[Goldie Lookin Chain]] for their 2005 album, ''Straight Outta Newport;''<ref>{{cite web|url=https://pitchfork.com/reviews/albums/3674-straight-outta-newport/|title=Goldie Lookin' Chain|work=Pitchfork|accessdate=August 14, 2015}}</ref> [[\"Weird Al\" Yankovic]]'s 2006 album, ''[[Straight Outta Lynwood]];'' and Australian grindcore band [[Blood Duster]]'s 1997 album ''Str8 Outta Northcote''. [[Punk rock]] band [[NOFX]] released a song, \"Straight Outta Massachusetts\", on their ''[[Cokie the Clown]]'' [[Extended play|EP]]. In the 2014 film ''[[22 Jump Street]]'', Mrs. Dickson states that she's \"straight outta Compton\" when talking about her and her husband's (played by Ice Cube) backgrounds.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://popwatch.ew.com/2014/06/14/22-jump-street-references/|title='22 Jump Street': 10 pop-culture references you might have missed|work=Entertainment Weekly's EW.com|accessdate=August 14, 2015}}</ref> In 2015, a [[biopic]] 'about the group, '[[Straight Outta Compton (film)|Straight Outta Compton]]'', was released.<ref>{{cite news| work= The Guardian| url= https://www.theguardian.com/film/2015/sep/02/straight-outta-compton-reel-history-nwa-eazy-e-ice-cube-dr-dre| title= Straight Outta Compton: hit biopic raps up NWA story cleanly| first= Alex |last= von Tunzelmann| date= 2015-09-02| access-date= 2020-03-11}}</ref>\n\n==Artwork==\nThe Miracle Mile Shot is a still photograph of N.W.A. created by L.A. photographer/artist [[Ithaka Darin Pappas]], that was used as the official press photo for the album. It was subsequently printed in hundreds of newspapers and magazines during 1989, including the May 1989 cover of [[The Source]] to illustrate the article, \"California Rap Hits Nationwide!\".<ref>{{Cite web | url=http://www.lamag.com/culturefiles/this-is-fresh-two-90s-era-hip-hop-films-revive-l-a-s-rap-glory-days/ | title=Two '90s-Era Hip Hop Films Revive L.A.'s Rap Glory Days Los Angeles Magazine| date=June 8, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web | url=https://www.massdrop.com/buy/image-club-limited |title = Drop: Passions lead here (Formerly Massdrop)}}</ref><ref name=\"latimes\">{{cite web|url=https://www.latimes.com/local/la-hp-notable-anniversaries-2013-20131214-007-photo.html|publisher=latimes.com|title=25th anniversary of &apos;Straight Outta Compton&apos; by N.W.A \u2013 LA Times|accessdate=2017-04-06}}</ref><ref name=\"lamag\">{{cite web|url=http://www.lamag.com/culturefiles/this-is-fresh-two-90s-era-hip-hop-films-revive-l-a-s-rap-glory-days/|publisher=lamag.com|title=Two &#039;90s-Era Hip Hop Films Revive L.A.&#039;s Rap Glory Days \u2013 Los Angeles Magazine|accessdate=2017-04-06|date=June 8, 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"vibe\">{{cite web|url=http://www.vibe.com/2014/06/former-n-w-a-manager-disappointed-with-biopic/|publisher=vibe.com|title=Former N.W.A Manager Disappointed With Biopic|accessdate=2017-04-06|date=June 30, 2014}}</ref>\n\nSince 2013 (the 25th anniversary of Straight Outta Compton) and the 2015 release of Universal's feature film ''Straight Outta Compton'' about N.W.A., the image has been republished in ''Rolling Stone'', ''Q Magazine'' (UK), [[The Hundreds]], [[Mass Appeal (media)|Mass Appeal]], ''[[Los Angeles (magazine)|Los Angeles]]'', ''[[Los Angeles Times]]'', ''Blitz Magazine'' (Portugal) and many others, and was used as the primary backdrop for the entire NWA segment of the 2016 [[Rock and Roll Hall of Fame]] induction ceremony in [[Brooklyn]], [[New York City]], [[New York (state)|New York]].<ref name=\"digitalspy\">{{cite web| url= http://www.digitalspy.com/music/news/a790016/ice-cube-and-dr-dre-join-nwa-members-in-brooklyn-as-they-are-admitted-to-rock-roll-hall-of-fame/| work= digitalspy.com|title=Ice Cube and Dr Dre join NWA members in Brooklyn as they're admitted to Rock & Roll Hall of Fame| accessdate=2017-04-06|date=April 9, 2016}}</ref> The Miracle Mile Shot was used as the DVD cover of the 2015 documentary, Kings Of Compton.<ref name=\"cineoutsider\">{{cite web| url= http://www.cineoutsider.com/news/stories/15/12/151215.html|work= cineoutsider.com|title=Documentary NWA &amp; Eazy-E: Kings of Compton on DVD in January &#124; Cine Outsider|accessdate=2017-04-06}}</ref><ref name=\"music-news\">{{cite web |url= http://www.music-news.com/news/UK/94264/NWA-Eazy-E-The-Kings-of-Compton-coming-to-DVD|publisher=music-news.com|title=NWA &amp; Eazy-E: The Kings of Compton coming to DVD | website= Music-News.com|accessdate=2017-04-06}}</ref><ref name=\"hmv\">{{cite web| url=http://store.hmv.com/film-tv/dvd/n-w-a-eazy-e-the-kings-of-compton| work= hmv.com|title=N.W.A & Eazy-E: The Kings of Compton : DVD &#124; HMV Store|accessdate=2017-04-06}}</ref><ref name=\"cinemablend\">{{cite web| url= https://www.cinemablend.com/new/NWA-Biopic-Straight-Outta-Compton-Has-Found-Its-Lead-Actors-43496.html| work= cinemablend.com|title=The NWA Biopic Straight Outta Compton Has Found Its Lead Actors |accessdate=2017-04-06|date=June 17, 2014}}</ref>\n\nFrom Early 2017 until January 2018, The Miracle Mile Shot appeared in the group hip hop photography and culture show, \"Hip-Hop : un Age d'Or 1970\u20131995\" (Hip Hop Golden Age 1970\u20131995), at the Mus\u00e9e d'art contemporain de Marseille in France. The exhibition was curated by artist and hip hop historian, [[Siba Giba]] and museum director, Thierry Ollat.<ref name=\"hiphopgoldenage\">{{cite web|url=http://hiphopgoldenage.com/artists/n-w-a/|publisher=hiphopgoldenage.com|title=N.W.A. \u2013 Hip Hop Golden Age Hip Hop Golden Age|accessdate=2017-04-06}}</ref><ref name=\"petitfute\">{{cite web|url=https://www.petitfute.com/v33156-33310-marseille-13008/c1170-manifestation-evenement/c245-exposition/1600765-hip-hop-un-age-d-or-1970-1995.html| work= petitfute.com|title=Exposition \u2013 HIP-HOP : UN \u00c2GE D'OR 1970\u20131995 \u2013 Marseille|accessdate=2017-04-06}}</ref><ref name=\"marseille\">{{cite web|url=http://living.marseille.fr/agenda/hip-hop-un-age-d-or-1970-1995-13evt074961/| work= living.marseille.fr|title=Hip-Hop : un \u00e2ge d'or 1970\u20131995 &#8211; Living Marseille|accessdate=2017-04-06|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20171213102854/http://living.marseille.fr/agenda/hip-hop-un-age-d-or-1970-1995-13evt074961/|archive-date=December 13, 2017|url-status=dead|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\nThe Miracle Mile Shot was made on November 11, 1988 at the photographer's small studio-apartment in the Miracle Mile district of Los Angeles. During the same session promotional images of the young female rapper, Big Lady K, and images of Eazy E to promote his album, Eazy-Duz-It (released almost simultaneously with Straight Outta Compton) were also made to promote his album ''Eazy-er Said Than Dunn''.<ref name=\"massappeal\">{{cite web|url=https://massappeal.com/contact-high-ithaka-darin-pappas-on-photographing-a-bulletproof-vest-wearing-skateboarding-riding-eazy-e/|publisher=massappeal.com|title=Mass Appeal \u2014Contact High: Ithaka Darin Pappas On Photographing a Bulletproof Vest-Wearing, Skateboarding-Riding Eazy-E|accessdate=2017-04-06|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170820034336/https://massappeal.com/contact-high-ithaka-darin-pappas-on-photographing-a-bulletproof-vest-wearing-skateboarding-riding-eazy-e/|archive-date=August 20, 2017|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref name=\"generaladmission.us\">/www.generaladmission.us/blogs/news/eazy-e-and-ithakas-iconic-photo</ref>\n\nOf the only two or three rolls of film made of N.W.A as a group that day, The Miracle Mile Shot was selected as the press image. It is the only existing image of all five prominent members of the group; [[DJ Yella]], [[Dr. Dre]], [[Eazy E]], [[Ice Cube]] and [[MC Ren]] without sunglasses and all looking at the camera.\n\n==Track listing==\n* All songs were produced by [[Dr. Dre]] and [[DJ Yella]]\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n! scope=\"col\" |No.\n! scope=\"col\" |Title\n! scope=\"col\" |Writer(s)\n! scope=\"col\" |Performer(s)\n! scope=\"col\" |Samples<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://secondhandsongs.com/release/7605|title=Tracks on Straight Outta Compton \u2013 N.W.A. (1988) {{!}} SecondHandSongs|website=secondhandsongs.com|access-date=2016-11-14}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title = N.W.A. \u2013 WhoSampled|url = http://www.whosampled.com/N.W.A/|website = WhoSampled|accessdate = 11 August 2015}}</ref>\n! scope=\"col\" |Length\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|1\n|\"[[Straight Outta Compton (song)|Straight Outta Compton]]\"\n|\n*[[Ice Cube]]\n*[[MC Ren]]\n*[[The D.O.C.]]\n\n| \n*Ice Cube\n*MC Ren\n*Eazy-E \n|\n* \"[[Funky Drummer]]\" by [[James Brown]]\n* \"You'll Like It Too\" by [[Funkadelic]]\n* \"West Coast Poplock\" by Ronnie Hudson and the Street People\n* \"Get Me Back on Time, Engine No. 9\" by [[Wilson Pickett]]\n* \"[[Amen, Brother]]\" by [[The Winstons]]\n* \"One for the Treble\" by [[Davy DMX]]\n\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|4:18\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|2\n|\"[[Fuck tha Police]]\"<ref>On the album, the obscenity is covered.</ref>\n|\n*Ice Cube\n*MC Ren\n|\n*Ice Cube\n*MC Ren\n*Eazy-E\n|\n* \"[[Funky President (People It's Bad)]]\" by [[James Brown]]\n* \"It's My Thing\" by [[Marva Whitney]]\n* \"Boogie Back\" by [[Roy Ayers]]\n* \"Feel Good\" by Fancy\n* \"[[Funky Drummer]]\" by [[James Brown]]\n* \"Ruthless Villain\" by [[Eazy-E]]\n* \"[[Be Thankful for What You Got]]\" by [[William DeVaughn]]\n\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|5:45\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|3\n|\"[[Gangsta Gangsta (N.W.A song)|Gangsta Gangsta]]\"\n|\n*Ice Cube\n*MC Ren\n*The D.O.C.\n|\n*Ice Cube\n*Eazy-E\n*MC Ren\n|\n* \"Weak at the Knees\" by [[Steve Arrington]]\n* \"Troglodyte\" by [[Jimmy Castor Bunch]]\n* \"[[Be Thankful for What You Got]]\" by [[William DeVaughn]]\n* \"Impeach the President\" by [[The Honey Drippers (soul band)|The Honey Drippers]]\n* \"N.T.\" by [[Kool & the Gang]]\n* \"[[Funky Worm]]\" by [[Ohio Players]]\n* \"Prison\" by [[Richard Pryor]]\n* \"My Philosophy\" by [[Boogie Down Productions]] ([[KRS-One]])\n* \"[[La Di Da Di]]\" by [[Doug E. Fresh]] and [[Slick Rick]]\n* \"[[Girls (Beastie Boys song)|Girls]]\" by [[Beastie Boys]]\n* \"Ruthless Villain\" by Eazy-E\n* \"[[Take the Money and Run (song)|Take the Money and Run]]\" by [[Steve Miller Band]]\n\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|5:36\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|4\n|\"If It Ain't Ruff\"\n|\n*MC Ren\n|\n*MC Ren\n|\n* \"A Star in the Ghetto\" by [[Average White Band]]\n* \"Quiet on tha Set\" and \"Straight Outta Compton\" by [[N.W.A]]\n* \"Ruthless Villain\" by Eazy-E\n* \"[[Don't Believe the Hype]]\" by [[Public Enemy (band)|Public Enemy]]\n\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|3:34\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|5\n|\"Parental Discretion Iz Advised\"\n|\n*The D.O.C. (also for Dr. Dre)\n*MC Ren\n*Ice Cube\n|\n*The D.O.C.\n*Dr. Dre\n*MC Ren\n*Ice Cube \n*Eazy-E\n|\n* \"[[I Turned You On]]\" by [[The Isley Brothers]] and [[Dave \"Baby\" Cortez]]\n\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|5:15\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|6\n|\"8 Ball (Remix)\"\n|\n*Ice Cube\n|\n*Eazy-E\n|\n* \"It's My Beat\" by Sweet Tea\n* \"[[Be Thankful for What You Got]]\" by [[William DeVaughn]]\n* \"Yes, We Can Can\" by [[The Pointer Sisters]]\n* \"[[(You Gotta) Fight for Your Right (To Party!)]]\", \"[[The New Style (song)|The New Style]]\", \"[[Girls (Beastie Boys song)|Girls]]\", \"[[Paul Revere (song)|Paul Revere]]\", and \"[[Hold It Now, Hit It]]\" by [[Beastie Boys]]\n* \"Terminator X Speaks With His Hands\" and \"Too Much Posse\" by Public Enemy\n* \"[[Hollywood Swinging]]\" by Kool & the Gang\n* \"[[Let's Get It On]]\" by [[Marvin Gaye]]\n* \"Go See the Doctor\" by [[Kool Moe Dee]]\n* \"[[Boyz-n-the-Hood]]\" by Eazy-E\n* \"My Melody\" by [[Eric B. & Rakim]]\n\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|4:52\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|7\n|\"Something Like That\"\n|\n*MC Ren (also for Dr. Dre)\n|\n*MC Ren\n*Dr. Dre\n|\n* \"Down on the Avenue\" by [[Fat Larry's Band]]\n* \"Take the Money and Run\" by [[Steve Miller Band]]\n* \"I Think I'll Do It\" by [[Z. Z. Hill]]\n\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|3:35\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:ce