{"title_page": "Roman Catholic Diocese of Palangkaraya", "text_new": "{{Infobox diocese\n|jurisdiction     = Diocese \n|name             = Palangkaraya \n|latin            = Di\u0153cesis Palangkaraiensis \n|local            = Keuskupan Palangkaraya\n|country          = [[Indonesia]]\n|metropolitan     = [[Roman Catholic Archdiocese of Samarinda|Samarinda]] \n|province         = [[Roman Catholic Archdiocese of Samarinda|Samarinda]]\n|rite             = [[Latin Rite]]\n|cathedral        = Cathedral of St Mary in [[Palangkaraya]]\n|cocathedral      = \n|area_km2         = 153,564  \n|population       = 2,332,864  \n|population_as_of = 2004  \n|catholics        = 53,585 \n|catholics_percent= 2.3  \n|pope             = {{Incumbent pope}}\n|bishop           = [[Aloysius Maryadi Sutrisnaatmaka]], [[Missionaries of the Holy Family|M.S.F.]] \n|metro_archbishop = [[Yustinus Harjosusanto]]\n|coadjutor        = \n|auxiliary_bishops= \n|website          = {{URL|kepraya.org}}\n}}\n\nThe '''Roman Catholic Diocese of Palangkaraya''' ({{lang-la| Palangkaraien(sis)}}) is a [[diocese]] located in the city of [[Palangkaraya]] in the [[Ecclesiastical province]] of [[Roman Catholic Archdiocese of Samarinda|Samarinda]] in Indonesia.\n\n==History==\n* April 5, 1993: Established as the Diocese of Palangkaraya from the [[Diocese of Banjarmasin]]\n\n==Leadership==\n* [[Bishop]]s of Palangkaraya (Roman rite)\n** Bishop Aloysius Maryadi Sutrisnaatmaka, M.S.F. (January 23, 2001 \u2013 present)\n** Bishop [[Yulius Aloysius Husin]], M.S.F. (April 5, 1993 \u2013 October 13, 1994)\n\n==References==\n* [http://www.gcatholic.org/dioceses/diocese/pala2.htm GCatholic.org]\n* [http://www.catholic-hierarchy.org/diocese/dplng.html Catholic Hierarchy]\n\n{{coord missing|Indonesia}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Palangkaraya}}\n[[Category:Roman Catholic dioceses in Indonesia]]\n[[Category:Christian organizations established in 1993]]\n[[Category:Palangkaraya]]\n[[Category:Roman Catholic dioceses and prelatures established in the 20th century]]\n\n{{Indonesia-stub}}\n{{Asia-RC-diocese-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox diocese\n|jurisdiction     = Diocese \n|name             = Palangkaraya \n|latin            = Dioecesis Palangkaraiensis \n|local            = Keuskupan Palangkaraya\n|country          = [[Indonesia]]\n|metropolitan     = [[Roman Catholic Archdiocese of Samarinda|Samarinda]] \n|province         = [[Roman Catholic Archdiocese of Samarinda|Samarinda]]\n|rite             = [[Latin Rite]]\n|cathedral        = Cathedral of St Mary in [[Palangkaraya]]\n|cocathedral      = \n|area_km2         = 153,564  \n|population       = 2,332,864  \n|population_as_of = 2004  \n|catholics        = 53,585 \n|catholics_percent= 2.3  \n|pope             = {{Incumbent pope}}\n|bishop           = [[Aloysius Maryadi Sutrisnaatmaka]], [[Missionaries of the Holy Family|M.S.F.]] \n|metro_archbishop = [[Sede Vacante]]\n|coadjutor        = \n|auxiliary_bishops= \n|website          = \n}}\n\nThe '''Roman Catholic Diocese of Palangkaraya''' ({{lang-la| Palangkaraien(sis)}}) is a [[diocese]] located in the city of [[Palangkaraya]] in the [[Ecclesiastical province]] of [[Roman Catholic Archdiocese of Samarinda|Samarinda]] in Indonesia.\n\n==History==\n* April 5, 1993: Established as the Diocese of Palangkaraya from the [[Diocese of Banjarmasin]]\n\n==Leadership==\n* [[Bishop]]s of Palangkaraya (Roman rite)\n** Bishop Aloysius Maryadi Sutrisnaatmaka, M.S.F. (January 23, 2001 \u2013 present)\n** Bishop [[Yulius Aloysius Husin]], M.S.F. (April 5, 1993 \u2013 October 13, 1994)\n\n==References==\n* [http://www.gcatholic.org/dioceses/diocese/pala2.htm GCatholic.org]\n* [http://www.catholic-hierarchy.org/diocese/dplng.html Catholic Hierarchy]\n\n{{coord missing|Indonesia}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Palangkaraya}}\n[[Category:Roman Catholic dioceses in Indonesia]]\n[[Category:Christian organizations established in 1993]]\n[[Category:Palangkaraya]]\n[[Category:Roman Catholic dioceses and prelatures established in the 20th century]]\n\n{{Indonesia-stub}}\n{{Asia-RC-diocese-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Azmi1995", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Roman_Catholic_Diocese_of_Palangkaraya"}
{"title_page": "Howard A. Rodman", "text_new": "{{Infobox person\n| name = Howard A. Rodman\n\n| caption = \n| birth_name = \n| birth_date = \n| birth_place = \n|occupation = screenwriter<br> author <br> educator\n| known_for   =  ''[[Savage Grace]]''<br> ''[[August (2008 film)|August]]''<br>''[[Joe Gould's Secret (film)]]''<br>''Destiny Express''<br>''The Great Eastern''\n}}\n'''Howard A. Rodman''' is a  [[screenwriter]], [[author]] and [[educator]]. He is the former President of the [[Writers Guild of America, West]], professor and former chair of the writing division at the [[USC School of Cinematic Arts]],<ref>{{Cite web|title=USC School of Cinematic Arts Directory Profile|url=http://cinema.usc.edu/faculty/profile.cfm?id=6619&first=&last=&title=&did=19&referer=facultydirectory.cfm&startpage=1&startrow=31}}</ref> and an artistic director of the [[Sundance Institute]] Screenwriting Labs.<ref>{{Cite web|title=Sundance Institute|url=http://history.sundance.org/people/24164}}</ref> He is the son of screenwriter Howard Rodman (1920\u20131985).\n\n==Career==\nIn his 20s and early 30s Rodman was a typist, a legal proofreader, a mail-room clerk, a union organizer (for the Committee of Interns and Residents) and the guitarist for various lower-Manhattan post-punk bands (Made in USA, Arsenal, Soul Sharks).<ref>http://cinema.usc.edu/faculty/profile.cfm?id=6619</ref><ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.huffingtonpost.com/howard-a-rodman | work=Huffington Post | title=Howard A. Rodman}}</ref> Starting as editor-in-chief of ''[[The Cornell Daily Sun]]'',<ref>{{Cite web|title=The Cornell Daily Sun|url=http://cornellsun.com/node/16695|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://archive.is/20130120030158/http://cornellsun.com/node/16695|archivedate=2013-01-20}}</ref> Rodman has published scores of articles in venues including ''The New York Times'',<ref>{{Cite news|title=The New York Times|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1971/05/27/archives/jaywalking-with-a-twotime-loser.html | first=Howard A. | last=Rodman|date=May 27, 1971}}</ref> ''The Los Angeles Times'',<ref>{{Cite news|title=The Los Angeles Times|url=https://www.latimes.com/news/la-oe-rodman17oct17,0,1677290.story | first=Howard A. | last=Rodman|date=October 17, 2007}}</ref> ''Los Angeles Magazine'',<ref>{{Cite web|title=Los Angeles Magazine|url=http://www.lamag.com/features/author/howard-a-rodman|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140222031456/http://www.lamag.com/features/author/howard-a-rodman|archivedate=2014-02-22}}</ref> and the ''Village Voice'' (for which he was a monthly columnist).<ref>{{Cite news|title=Variety|url=https://www.variety.com/article/VR1117866448?refCatId=14}}</ref>\n\nHis adaptations of Jim Thompson, David Goodis et al. for Showtime's ''[[Fallen Angels (American TV series)|Fallen Angels]]'' anthology series<ref>{{Cite web|title=Fallen Angels|url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0105994/fullcredits#cast}}</ref> were directed by [[Steven Soderbergh]] and [[Tom Cruise]]. Rodman then wrote ''[[Joe Gould's Secret (film)|Joe Gould's Secret]]'', which opened the 2000 Sundance festival and was subsequently released by October/USA Films. Rodman's original screenplay ''F.'' was selected by ''Premiere Magazine'' as one of Hollywood's Ten Best Unproduced Screenplays.<ref>{{Cite web|title=BAFTA Events Archive|url=http://www.baftala.org/screenings/archive/index.php?page=17&type=event&year=}}</ref> Other films include ''[[Savage Grace]]'', starring Julianne Moore, and ''[[August (2008 film)|August]]'', with Josh Hartnett, Rip Torn, and David Bowie\u2014both of which had their US premieres at the [[List of films at the 2008 Sundance Film Festival|2008 Sundance Film Festival]]. They were released in 2008 from IFC and First Look, respectively. Rodman's screenplay for ''Savage Grace'' was nominated for a Spirit Award in the Best Screenplay category.\n\n== ''Destiny Express'' ==\n\n[[File:Destiny Express by Howard Rodman.jpg|thumb|Dust jacket of 'Destiny Express',  a novel by Howard A. Rodman. Blurb by [[Thomas Pynchon]] visible ]]\nHis novel 'Destiny Express', an historical romance set in the pre-war German film community, was published in January 1990 by [[Atheneum Books]]. <ref>https://isbnsearch.org/isbn/9780689120909</ref>\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n== ''The Great Eastern'' ==\n\n[[File:Book and Kindle editions of 'The Great Eastern' by Howard A. Rodman.jpg|thumb|Book and Kindle editions of 'The Great Eastern' by Howard A. Rodman. \n]]\nThe novel ''[[The Great Eastern (Rodman novel)|The Great Eastern]]'' by Howard A. Rodman was published<ref>https://www.mhpbooks.com/books/the-great-eastern/</ref> on June 4, 2019, by [[Melville House Publishing]]. \n\nIn March 2019, the film rights to ''The Great Eastern'' were acquired by the UK film company Great Point Media, and Rodman was commissioned to write the screen adaptation.<ref>{{Cite magazine |title=Howard A. Rodman\u2019s Book \u2018The Great Eastern\u2019 to Be Adapted Into Movie|url=https://variety.com/2019/film/news/howard-a-rodman-great-eastern-movie-1203163719/ |magazine=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]}}</ref>\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n== Reviews ==\n*{{cite news| url=https://lareviewofbooks.org/article/past-and-pastiche-in-howard-a-rodmans-the-great-eastern/| title=Past and Pastiche in Howard A. Rodman\u2019s \u201cThe Great Eastern\u201d| author=[[Brian Evenson]]| date=July 15, 2019| work=Los Angeles Review of Books}}\n*{{cite news| url=https://nbmagazine.co.uk/the-great-eastern-by-howard-a-rodman/| title= \"The Great Eastern\" by Howard A. Rodman| author=[[Paul Burke]]{{dn|date=February 2020}}| date=June 15, 2019 || work=NB Magazine}}\n*{{cite news| url=http://thetangential.com/2019/07/17/book-review-howard-rodmans-the-great-eastern-pits-ahab-against-nemo/| title= Howard Rodman\u2019s \u201cThe Great Eastern\u201d Pits Ahab Against Nemo| author=[[Jay Gabler]]| date=July 17, 2019| work=The Tangential}}\n\n== Other activities ==\nHe founded and chairs the Writers Guild Independent Writers Caucus.<ref>{{Cite web|title=WGAW The Independent Writers Caucus (IWC)|url=http://www.wga.org/subpage_writersresources.aspx?id=925|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121006045406/http://wga.org/subpage_writersresources.aspx?id=925|archivedate=2012-10-06}}</ref> He has chaired FilmIndependent's Spirit Awards feature film jury<ref>{{Cite web|title=Movieweb|url=http://www.movieweb.com/news/2007-film-independents-spirit-awards-nominations-announced}}</ref> as well as the USC Scripter Awards.<ref>{{Cite web|title=25th Annual USC Libraries Scripter Award|url=http://www.usc.edu/libraries/scripter/}}</ref> He is a Fellow of the Los Angeles Institute for the Humanities;<ref>{{Cite web|title=LAIH Fellows, Howard A. Rodman|url=http://www.usc.edu/libraries/partners/laih/fellows/HowardA.Rodman.htm}}</ref> a member of the executive committee of the writers' branch of the Academy of Motion Picture Arts and Sciences;<ref>{{Cite web|title=Academy Invites 134 to Membership|url=http://www.oscars.org/press/pressreleases/2009/20090630.html}}</ref> a former trustee of the Writers Guild Foundation;<ref>{{Cite web|title=Writers Guild Foundation Staff & Board|url=https://www.wgfoundation.org/about-us-writers-community/staff-and-board/}}</ref> vice-chair of the Committee on the Professional Status of Writers;<ref>{{Cite news|title=The Hollywood Reporter, WGAW 2011 Elections|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/lists/howard-a-rodman-228632 | first=Jonathan | last=Handel|date=August 28, 2011}}</ref> and serves on several nonprofit boards, among them the Franco-American Cultural Fund,<ref>{{Cite web|title=16th Annual City of Lights City of Angels Film Festival|url=http://www.zimbio.com/photos/Howard+A.+Rodman/16th+Annual+City+Lights+City+Angels+Film+Festival/VuLk3f7K9Yv}}</ref> and Cornell in Hollywood.<ref>{{Cite web|title=Cornell Alumni Magazine|url=http://cornellalumnimagazine.com/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=485&Itemid=56&ed=12}}</ref> He is an alumnus of the Seed Fund Board of the [[Liberty Hill Foundation]],<ref>{{Cite web|title=Liberty Hill Foundation|url=http://www.libertyhill.org/page.aspx?pid=586}}</ref> and a former editor of ''The Bill of Rights Journal''.<ref>{{Cite web|title=The Bill of Rights Journal N.E.C.L.C. 25th Anniversary December 1976|url=https://www.amazon.com/dp/B002DTA1P0}}</ref>\n\nHoward is also on Los Angeles committee of PEN America<ref>https://pen.org/los-angeles-committee/</ref>. [[PEN International]] stands at the intersection of literature and human rights to protect free expression in the United States and worldwide.<ref>https://pen.org/about-us/</ref>\n\nHe is a member of the National Film Preservation Board, which advises Librarian of Congress on the annual selection of films to the National Film Registry. It also advises on national film preservation planning policy.<ref>https://www.loc.gov/static/programs/national-film-preservation-board/documents/NFPB_Members_1988-2019.pdf</ref>\n\nWorking with the Library Foundation of Los Angeles<ref>https://lfla.org/event/dictionaries-and-the-bending-of-language/</ref>, USC<ref>https://cinema.usc.edu/faculty/profile.cfm?id=6619&first=&last=&title=&did=50&referer=%2Ffaculty%2Ffacultydirectory.cfm&startpage=1&startrow=181</ref>, and the Writers Guild<ref>https://www.wga.org/the-guild/about-us/history/presidents</ref>, Rodman has conducted public conversations with such writers as Tom Wolfe<ref>https://www.lapl.org/collections-resources/e-media/podcasts/aloud/evening-tom-wolfe</ref>, Ricky Jay, Jeannette Seaver, Vince Gilligan, Geoff Dyer, and Lady Antonia Fraser.<ref>https://www.lapl.org/collections-resources/e-media/podcasts/aloud/must-you-go-my-life-harold-pinter</ref><ref>https://cinema.usc.edu/faculty/profile.cfm?id=6619&first=&last=&title=&did=50&referer=%2Ffaculty%2Ffacultydirectory.cfm&startpage=1&startrow=181</ref>\n\nIn November 2019, he was a member of the jury<ref>https://www.festivalcannes1939.com/the-jury</ref> at the Cannes 1939 Film Festival in Orl\u00e9ans France.<ref>https://www.festivalcannes1939.com/1st-cannes-film-festival-1939</ref>\n\nHoward Rodman also contributes to the [[Los Angeles Review of Books]]<ref>https://lareviewofbooks.org/contributor/howard-a-rodman</ref>. His latest articles include '[http://After%20Hours%20Capitalism:%20On%20Tom%20Lutz\u2019s%20\u201cBorn%20Slippy After Hours Capitalism: On Tom Lutz\u2019s \u201cBorn Slippy]\u201d'<ref>https://lareviewofbooks.org/article/after-hours-capitalism-on-tom-lutzs-born-slippy/</ref> a review of [[Tom Lutz]]\u2019s \u201cBorn Slippy\u201d<ref>https://repeaterbooks.com/product/born-slippy-a-novel/</ref>, published by [[Repeater Books]] and [https://blog.lareviewofbooks.org/essays/192nd-anniversary-birth-jules-verne/ 'On the 192nd Anniversary of the Birth of Jules Verne'.]\n\n==Honors and awards==\nOn October 31, 2013, Rodman was named a Chevalier de [[l'Ordre des Arts et des Lettres]] by the French Republic.<ref>https://www.deadline.com/2013/10/global-showbiz-briefs-broadchurch-book-the-escape-artist-sales-bassem-youssef-louis-delluc-shortlist-more/</ref>\n\nIn February 2018 he was inducted into [[Final Draft (software)]]'s Screenwriters Hall of Fame,<ref>{{Cite news|title=Final Draft Awards to Honor 'The Post's' Liz Hannah and Former WGA West Chief Howard Rodman|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/race/final-draft-awards-posts-liz-hannah-wga-west-president-howard-rodman-be-honored-10776684 | work=Hollywood Reporter | first=Scoott|last=Feinberg|date=January 23, 2018}}</ref> alongside [[Robert Towne]], [[Steven Zaillian]], [[Aaron Sorkin]], [[Nancy Meyers]], [[Paul Schrader]], [[Lawrence Kasdan]] et al.\n\n==Personal life==\nHe was married to the writer and media scholar [[Anne Friedberg]],<ref>{{Cite news|title=Anne Friedberg dies at 57; professor at USC's School of Cinematic Arts|url=https://articles.latimes.com/2009/oct/14/local/me-anne-friedberg14 | work=Los Angeles Times | first=Elaine|last=Woo|date=October 14, 2009}}</ref> author of ''The Virtual Window''.<ref>{{Cite web|title=The MIT Press: The Virtual Window|url=http://mitpress.mit.edu/catalog/item/default.asp?tid=10780&ttype=2|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120921044639/http://mitpress.mit.edu/catalog/item/default.asp?ttype=2&tid=10780|archivedate=2012-09-21}}</ref> until her death in 2009; they have one son, Tristan Rodman. Their house, the 1957 [[John Lautner]] \"Zahn Residence,\" has been widely published. Their work with Lautner in restoring it was chronicled in the February 2002 issue of ''Dwell'' magazine.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Dwell|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=MsQDAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA50&lpg=PA50&dq=zahn+dwell+rodman&source=bl&ots=HnogF41Ebw&sig=W9AeIlF5vQ3roYrt7yz9K-Q56s4&hl=en&sa=X&ei=2_xyUNb-KsHviQKKuYDABA&ved=0CCAQ6AEwAA#v=onepage&q=zahn%20dwell%20rodman&f=false}}</ref>  In June 2017 he wed the artist and professor Mary Beth Heffernan.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{IMDb name|0734912}}\n* [http://cinema.usc.edu/faculty/profile.cfm?id=6619&first=&last=&title=&did=19&referer=facultydirectory.cfm&startpage=1&startrow=31 Howard Rodman's USC faculty page]\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Rodman, Howard A.}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Los Angeles]]\n[[Category:American male screenwriters]]\n[[Category:20th-century American novelists]]\n[[Category:American instructional writers]]\n[[Category:Screenwriters from California]]\n[[Category:American male novelists]]\n[[Category:American television writers]]\n[[Category:Male television writers]]\n[[Category:University of Southern California faculty]]\n[[Category:Chevaliers of the Ordre des Arts et des Lettres]]\n[[Category:Screenwriting instructors]]\n[[Category:20th-century American male writers]]\n[[Category:Novelists from California]]\n[[Category:20th-century American non-fiction writers]]\n[[Category:American male non-fiction writers]]\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox person\n| name = Howard A. Rodman\n\n| caption = \n| birth_name = \n| birth_date = \n| birth_place = \n|occupation = screenwriter<br> author <br> educator\n| known_for   =  ''[[Savage Grace]]''<br> ''[[August (2008 film)|August]]''<br>''[[Joe Gould's Secret (film)]]''<br>''Destiny Express''<br>''The Great Eastern''\n}}\n'''Howard A. Rodman''' is a  [[screenwriter]], [[author]] and [[educator]]. He is the former President of the [[Writers Guild of America, West]], professor and former chair of the writing division at the [[USC School of Cinematic Arts]],<ref>{{Cite web|title=USC School of Cinematic Arts Directory Profile|url=http://cinema.usc.edu/faculty/profile.cfm?id=6619&first=&last=&title=&did=19&referer=facultydirectory.cfm&startpage=1&startrow=31}}</ref> and an artistic director of the [[Sundance Institute]] Screenwriting Labs.<ref>{{Cite web|title=Sundance Institute|url=http://history.sundance.org/people/24164}}</ref> He is the son of screenwriter Howard Rodman (1920\u20131985).\n\n==Career==\nIn his 20s and early 30s Rodman was a typist, a legal proofreader, a mail-room clerk, a union organizer (for the Committee of Interns and Residents) and the guitarist for various lower-Manhattan post-punk bands (Made in USA, Arsenal, Soul Sharks).<ref>http://cinema.usc.edu/faculty/profile.cfm?id=6619</ref><ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.huffingtonpost.com/howard-a-rodman | work=Huffington Post | title=Howard A. Rodman}}</ref> Starting as editor-in-chief of ''[[The Cornell Daily Sun]]'',<ref>{{Cite web|title=The Cornell Daily Sun|url=http://cornellsun.com/node/16695|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://archive.is/20130120030158/http://cornellsun.com/node/16695|archivedate=2013-01-20}}</ref> Rodman has published scores of articles in venues including ''The New York Times'',<ref>{{Cite news|title=The New York Times|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1971/05/27/archives/jaywalking-with-a-twotime-loser.html | first=Howard A. | last=Rodman|date=May 27, 1971}}</ref> ''The Los Angeles Times'',<ref>{{Cite news|title=The Los Angeles Times|url=https://www.latimes.com/news/la-oe-rodman17oct17,0,1677290.story | first=Howard A. | last=Rodman|date=October 17, 2007}}</ref> ''Los Angeles Magazine'',<ref>{{Cite web|title=Los Angeles Magazine|url=http://www.lamag.com/features/author/howard-a-rodman|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140222031456/http://www.lamag.com/features/author/howard-a-rodman|archivedate=2014-02-22}}</ref> and the ''Village Voice'' (for which he was a monthly columnist).<ref>{{Cite news|title=Variety|url=https://www.variety.com/article/VR1117866448?refCatId=14}}</ref>\n\nHis adaptations of Jim Thompson, David Goodis et al. for Showtime's ''[[Fallen Angels (American TV series)|Fallen Angels]]'' anthology series<ref>{{Cite web|title=Fallen Angels|url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0105994/fullcredits#cast}}</ref> were directed by [[Steven Soderbergh]] and [[Tom Cruise]]. Rodman then wrote ''[[Joe Gould's Secret (film)|Joe Gould's Secret]]'', which opened the 2000 Sundance festival and was subsequently released by October/USA Films. Rodman's original screenplay ''F.'' was selected by ''Premiere Magazine'' as one of Hollywood's Ten Best Unproduced Screenplays.<ref>{{Cite web|title=BAFTA Events Archive|url=http://www.baftala.org/screenings/archive/index.php?page=17&type=event&year=}}</ref> Other films include ''[[Savage Grace]]'', starring Julianne Moore, and ''[[August (2008 film)|August]]'', with Josh Hartnett, Rip Torn, and David Bowie\u2014both of which had their US premieres at the [[List of films at the 2008 Sundance Film Festival|2008 Sundance Film Festival]]. They were released in 2008 from IFC and First Look, respectively. Rodman's screenplay for ''Savage Grace'' was nominated for a Spirit Award in the Best Screenplay category.\n\n== ''Destiny Express'' ==\n\n[[File:Destiny Express by Howard Rodman.jpg|thumb|Dust jacket of 'Destiny Express',  a novel by Howard A. Rodman. Blurb by [[Thomas Pynchon]] visible ]]\nHis novel 'Destiny Express', an historical romance set in the pre-war German film community, was published in January 1990 by [[Atheneum Books]]. <ref>https://isbnsearch.org/isbn/9780689120909</ref>\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n== ''The Great Eastern'' ==\n\n[[File:Book and Kindle editions of 'The Great Eastern' by Howard A. Rodman.jpg|thumb|Book and Kindle editions of 'The Great Eastern' by Howard A. Rodman. \n]]\nThe novel ''[[The Great Eastern (Rodman novel)|The Great Eastern]]'' by Howard A. Rodman was published<ref>https://www.mhpbooks.com/books/the-great-eastern/</ref> on June 4, 2019, by [[Melville House Publishing]]. \n\nIn March 2019, the film rights to ''The Great Eastern'' were acquired by the UK film company Great Point Media, and Rodman was commissioned to write the screen adaptation.<ref>{{Cite magazine |title=Howard A. Rodman\u2019s Book \u2018The Great Eastern\u2019 to Be Adapted Into Movie|url=https://variety.com/2019/film/news/howard-a-rodman-great-eastern-movie-1203163719/ |magazine=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]}}</ref>\n\n== Reviews ==\n*{{cite news| url=https://lareviewofbooks.org/article/past-and-pastiche-in-howard-a-rodmans-the-great-eastern/| title=Past and Pastiche in Howard A. Rodman\u2019s \u201cThe Great Eastern\u201d| author=[[Brian Evenson]]| date=July 15, 2019| work=Los Angeles Review of Books}}\n*{{cite news| url=https://nbmagazine.co.uk/the-great-eastern-by-howard-a-rodman/| title= \"The Great Eastern\" by Howard A. Rodman| author=[[Paul Burke]]{{dn|date=February 2020}}| date=June 15, 2019 || work=NB Magazine}}\n*{{cite news| url=http://thetangential.com/2019/07/17/book-review-howard-rodmans-the-great-eastern-pits-ahab-against-nemo/| title= Howard Rodman\u2019s \u201cThe Great Eastern\u201d Pits Ahab Against Nemo| author=[[Jay Gabler]]| date=July 17, 2019| work=The Tangential}}\n\n== Other activities ==\nHe founded and chairs the Writers Guild Independent Writers Caucus.<ref>{{Cite web|title=WGAW The Independent Writers Caucus (IWC)|url=http://www.wga.org/subpage_writersresources.aspx?id=925|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121006045406/http://wga.org/subpage_writersresources.aspx?id=925|archivedate=2012-10-06}}</ref> He has chaired FilmIndependent's Spirit Awards feature film jury<ref>{{Cite web|title=Movieweb|url=http://www.movieweb.com/news/2007-film-independents-spirit-awards-nominations-announced}}</ref> as well as the USC Scripter Awards.<ref>{{Cite web|title=25th Annual USC Libraries Scripter Award|url=http://www.usc.edu/libraries/scripter/}}</ref> He is a Fellow of the Los Angeles Institute for the Humanities;<ref>{{Cite web|title=LAIH Fellows, Howard A. Rodman|url=http://www.usc.edu/libraries/partners/laih/fellows/HowardA.Rodman.htm}}</ref> a member of the executive committee of the writers' branch of the Academy of Motion Picture Arts and Sciences;<ref>{{Cite web|title=Academy Invites 134 to Membership|url=http://www.oscars.org/press/pressreleases/2009/20090630.html}}</ref> a former trustee of the Writers Guild Foundation;<ref>{{Cite web|title=Writers Guild Foundation Staff & Board|url=https://www.wgfoundation.org/about-us-writers-community/staff-and-board/}}</ref> vice-chair of the Committee on the Professional Status of Writers;<ref>{{Cite news|title=The Hollywood Reporter, WGAW 2011 Elections|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/lists/howard-a-rodman-228632 | first=Jonathan | last=Handel|date=August 28, 2011}}</ref> and serves on several nonprofit boards, among them the Franco-American Cultural Fund,<ref>{{Cite web|title=16th Annual City of Lights City of Angels Film Festival|url=http://www.zimbio.com/photos/Howard+A.+Rodman/16th+Annual+City+Lights+City+Angels+Film+Festival/VuLk3f7K9Yv}}</ref> and Cornell in Hollywood.<ref>{{Cite web|title=Cornell Alumni Magazine|url=http://cornellalumnimagazine.com/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=485&Itemid=56&ed=12}}</ref> He is an alumnus of the Seed Fund Board of the [[Liberty Hill Foundation]],<ref>{{Cite web|title=Liberty Hill Foundation|url=http://www.libertyhill.org/page.aspx?pid=586}}</ref> and a former editor of ''The Bill of Rights Journal''.<ref>{{Cite web|title=The Bill of Rights Journal N.E.C.L.C. 25th Anniversary December 1976|url=https://www.amazon.com/dp/B002DTA1P0}}</ref>\n\nHoward is also on Los Angeles committee of PEN America<ref>https://pen.org/los-angeles-committee/</ref>. [[PEN International]] stands at the intersection of literature and human rights to protect free expression in the United States and worldwide.<ref>https://pen.org/about-us/</ref>\n\nHe is a member of the National Film Preservation Board, which advises Librarian of Congress on the annual selection of films to the National Film Registry. It also advises on national film preservation planning policy.<ref>https://www.loc.gov/static/programs/national-film-preservation-board/documents/NFPB_Members_1988-2019.pdf</ref>\n\nWorking with the Library Foundation of Los Angeles<ref>https://lfla.org/event/dictionaries-and-the-bending-of-language/</ref>, USC<ref>https://cinema.usc.edu/faculty/profile.cfm?id=6619&first=&last=&title=&did=50&referer=%2Ffaculty%2Ffacultydirectory.cfm&startpage=1&startrow=181</ref>, and the Writers Guild<ref>https://www.wga.org/the-guild/about-us/history/presidents</ref>, Rodman has conducted public conversations with such writers as Tom Wolfe<ref>https://www.lapl.org/collections-resources/e-media/podcasts/aloud/evening-tom-wolfe</ref>, Ricky Jay, Jeannette Seaver, Vince Gilligan, Geoff Dyer, and Lady Antonia Fraser.<ref>https://www.lapl.org/collections-resources/e-media/podcasts/aloud/must-you-go-my-life-harold-pinter</ref><ref>https://cinema.usc.edu/faculty/profile.cfm?id=6619&first=&last=&title=&did=50&referer=%2Ffaculty%2Ffacultydirectory.cfm&startpage=1&startrow=181</ref>\n\nIn November 2019, he was a member of the jury<ref>https://www.festivalcannes1939.com/the-jury</ref> at the Cannes 1939 Film Festival in Orl\u00e9ans France.<ref>https://www.festivalcannes1939.com/1st-cannes-film-festival-1939</ref>\n\nHoward Rodman also contributes to the [[Los Angeles Review of Books]]<ref>https://lareviewofbooks.org/contributor/howard-a-rodman</ref>. His latest articles include '[http://After%20Hours%20Capitalism:%20On%20Tom%20Lutz\u2019s%20\u201cBorn%20Slippy After Hours Capitalism: On Tom Lutz\u2019s \u201cBorn Slippy]\u201d'<ref>https://lareviewofbooks.org/article/after-hours-capitalism-on-tom-lutzs-born-slippy/</ref> a review of [[Tom Lutz]]\u2019s \u201cBorn Slippy\u201d<ref>https://repeaterbooks.com/product/born-slippy-a-novel/</ref>, published by [[Repeater Books]] and [https://blog.lareviewofbooks.org/essays/192nd-anniversary-birth-jules-verne/ 'On the 192nd Anniversary of the Birth of Jules Verne'.]\n\n==Honors and awards==\nOn October 31, 2013, Rodman was named a Chevalier de [[l'Ordre des Arts et des Lettres]] by the French Republic.<ref>https://www.deadline.com/2013/10/global-showbiz-briefs-broadchurch-book-the-escape-artist-sales-bassem-youssef-louis-delluc-shortlist-more/</ref>\n\nIn February 2018 he was inducted into [[Final Draft (software)]]'s Screenwriters Hall of Fame,<ref>{{Cite news|title=Final Draft Awards to Honor 'The Post's' Liz Hannah and Former WGA West Chief Howard Rodman|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/race/final-draft-awards-posts-liz-hannah-wga-west-president-howard-rodman-be-honored-10776684 | work=Hollywood Reporter | first=Scoott|last=Feinberg|date=January 23, 2018}}</ref> alongside [[Robert Towne]], [[Steven Zaillian]], [[Aaron Sorkin]], [[Nancy Meyers]], [[Paul Schrader]], [[Lawrence Kasdan]] et al.\n\n==Personal life==\nHe was married to the writer and media scholar [[Anne Friedberg]],<ref>{{Cite news|title=Anne Friedberg dies at 57; professor at USC's School of Cinematic Arts|url=https://articles.latimes.com/2009/oct/14/local/me-anne-friedberg14 | work=Los Angeles Times | first=Elaine|last=Woo|date=October 14, 2009}}</ref> author of ''The Virtual Window''.<ref>{{Cite web|title=The MIT Press: The Virtual Window|url=http://mitpress.mit.edu/catalog/item/default.asp?tid=10780&ttype=2|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120921044639/http://mitpress.mit.edu/catalog/item/default.asp?ttype=2&tid=10780|archivedate=2012-09-21}}</ref> until her death in 2009; they have one son, Tristan Rodman. Their house, the 1957 [[John Lautner]] \"Zahn Residence,\" has been widely published. Their work with Lautner in restoring it was chronicled in the February 2002 issue of ''Dwell'' magazine.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Dwell|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=MsQDAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA50&lpg=PA50&dq=zahn+dwell+rodman&source=bl&ots=HnogF41Ebw&sig=W9AeIlF5vQ3roYrt7yz9K-Q56s4&hl=en&sa=X&ei=2_xyUNb-KsHviQKKuYDABA&ved=0CCAQ6AEwAA#v=onepage&q=zahn%20dwell%20rodman&f=false}}</ref>  In June 2017 he wed the artist and professor Mary Beth Heffernan.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{IMDb name|0734912}}\n* [http://cinema.usc.edu/faculty/profile.cfm?id=6619&first=&last=&title=&did=19&referer=facultydirectory.cfm&startpage=1&startrow=31 Howard Rodman's USC faculty page]\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Rodman, Howard A.}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Los Angeles]]\n[[Category:American male screenwriters]]\n[[Category:20th-century American novelists]]\n[[Category:American instructional writers]]\n[[Category:Screenwriters from California]]\n[[Category:American male novelists]]\n[[Category:American television writers]]\n[[Category:Male television writers]]\n[[Category:University of Southern California faculty]]\n[[Category:Chevaliers of the Ordre des Arts et des Lettres]]\n[[Category:Screenwriting instructors]]\n[[Category:20th-century American male writers]]\n[[Category:Novelists from California]]\n[[Category:20th-century American non-fiction writers]]\n[[Category:American male non-fiction writers]]\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n", "name_user": "Amanda scott", "label": "safe", "comment": 