{"title_page": "Keith Ismael", "text_new": "{{Infobox college football player\n|name=Keith Ismael\n|school=San Diego State Aztecs\n|currentnumber=60\n|currentposition=[[Center (gridiron football)|Center]]\n|class=  Junior\n|major = \n|birth_date=\n|birth_place=\n|bowlgames=\n|heightft=6\n|heightin=3\n|weight_lb=310\n|highlights=\n|highschool=[[Sacred Heart Cathedral Preparatory|Sacred Heart Cathedral]]\n|pastschools=\n*[[San Diego State Aztecs football|San Diego State]] (2017\u20132019)\n|espn=\n}}\n\n'''Keith Ismael''' is an [[American football]] [[Center (gridiron football)|center]] for the [[San Diego State Aztecs football|San Diego State Aztecs]].\n\n==College career==\nIsmael was a three year starter at San Diego State. He was named second team All-Mountain West Conference as a freshman and to the first team as a sophomore and as a freshman. He announced he would forgo his senior season to enter the 2020 NFL Draft.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sandiegouniontribune.com/sports/aztecs/story/2019-12-23/san-diego-state-aztecs-sdsu-football-center-keith-ismael-declares-early-for-nfl-draft|title=Aztecs center Keith Ismael declares early for 2020 NFL Draft|date=December 24, 2019|website=San Diego Union-Tribune}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://goaztecs.com/sports/football/roster/keith-ismael/5715 San Diego State bio]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Ismael, Keith}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Players of American football from California]]\n[[Category:American football centers]]\n[[Category:San Diego State Aztecs football players]]\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox college football player\n|name=Keith Ismael\n|school=San Diego State Aztecs\n|currentnumber=60\n|currentposition=[[Center (gridiron football)|Center]]\n|class=  Junior\n|major = \n|birth_date=\n|birth_place=\n|bowlgames=\n|heightft=6\n|heightin=3\n|weight_lb=310\n|highlights=\n|highschool=[[Sacred Heart Cathedral Preparatory|Sacred Heart Cathedral]]\n|pastschools=\n*[[San Diego State Aztecs football|San Diego State]] (2017\u20132019)\n|espn=\n}}\n\n'''Keith Ismael''' is an [[American football]] [[Center (gridiron football)|center]] for the [[San Diego State Aztecs football|San Diego State Aztecs]].\n\n==College career==\nIsmael was a three year starter at San Diego State. He was named second team All-Mountain West Conference as a freshman and to the first team as a sophomore and as a freshman. He announced he would forgo his senior season to enter the 2020 NFL Draft.<ref>https://www.sandiegouniontribune.com/sports/aztecs/story/2019-12-23/san-diego-state-aztecs-sdsu-football-center-keith-ismael-declares-early-for-nfl-draft</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://goaztecs.com/sports/football/roster/keith-ismael/5715 San Diego State bio]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Ismael, Keith}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Players of American football from California]]\n[[Category:American football centers]]\n[[Category:San Diego State Aztecs football players]]\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n", "name_user": "CAPTAIN RAJU", "label": "safe", "comment": "Filled in 1 bare reference(s) with reFill 2", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Keith_Ismael"}
{"title_page": "Otto Ozols", "text_new": "'''Otto Ozols''' ([[J\u016brmala]], [[23 August]] [[1970]]), pen name of '''M\u0101rti\u0146\u0161 Barkovskis''', is a [[Latvian]] [[columnist]], [[writer]] and [[social activist]]. Ozols\u2019 first book, the novel  \u201cLatvie\u0161i ir visur\u201d (\u201cLatvians are Everywhere\u201d) became a bestseller in 2011<ref>{{cite web |title=Latvian literature |url=http://latvianliterature.lv/en/writers/76 |website=Otto Ozols |publisher=Latvian literature |accessdate=25 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Kalni\u0146\u0161 |first1=P\u0113teris |title=Claiming Latvians are everywhere, sweeping novel proves entertaining |url=https://latviansonline.com/claiming-latvians-are-everywhere-sweeping-novel-proves-entertaining/ |website=Latvians online |accessdate=25 April 2020}}</ref>, having gone through 11 reprints since then. He has written two more books, \"Theodorus. Deja ar zilo\u0146zivi\" (\"Theodorus. Dancing with the Elephant Fish\"), published in 2014 and described as \u201cEurope's answer to Britain's James Bond and America's Jason Bourne\u201d, and \"Ne\u0113rt\u0101s paties\u012bbas\" (Uncomfortable truths), a collection of Ozols\u2019 opinion pieces and articles on Latvian politics, published in 2015. Otto Ozols is also an actively engaged author of political essays and political analysis, for several years he was a regular columnist for the largest news portals of Latvia, TVNET <ref>{{cite web |title=TVNET |url=https://www.tvnet.lv/author/112003 |website=TVNET |accessdate=25 April 2020}}</ref>, DELFI <ref>{{cite web |title=Delfi Latvija |url=https://www.delfi.lv/temas/otto-ozols/ |website=Delfi.lv |publisher=Delfi.lv |accessdate=25 April 2020}}</ref> and LA.lv <ref>{{cite web |title=LA |url=https://www.la.lv/author/otto-ozols |website=LA.LV |publisher=LA.LV |accessdate=25 April 2020}}</ref>.\n\n== Social activism ==\nIn order to acquaint himself with the [[Catalan independence movement]], Otto Ozols in April 2016 became the first known person to traverse on foot the entire length of the [[Catalan Way]] \u2013 in 16 days, 480 km<ref>{{cite web |url=https://replay.lsm.lv/lv/ieraksts/lr/67564/rakstnieks-otto-ozols-katalonijas-cela |website=LSM.LV |accessdate=25 April 2020}}</ref>. Before doing this, he had written in September 2013 and article linking Catalan independence with the [[Baltic Way]] and Latvian Restoration Independence<ref>{{cite web |title=The Catalan Way (Via Catalana) is the way of tens of millions of Europeans |url=https://latviansonline.com/the-catalan-way-via-catalana-is-the-way-of-tens-of-millions-of-europeans/ |website=Latvians Online |accessdate=25 April 2020}}</ref>. He visited 68 villages and met with hundreds of individuals. In Barcelona, the capital city of Catalonia, he met with [[Carme Forcadell]], president of Catalonia\u2019s parliament at the time<ref>{{cite web |last1=Carme |first1=Forcadell |url=https://twitter.com/forcadellcarme/status/720542289483972608 |website=Twitter |publisher=Carme Forcadell |accessdate=25 April 2020}}</ref>. He is expected to publish a book of collected materials and impressions on his walking trip.\n\n== References ==\n", "text_old": "'''Otto Ozols''' ([[J\u016brmala]], [[23 August]] [[1970]]), pen name of '''M\u0101rti\u0146\u0161 Barkovskis''', is a [[Latvian]] [[columnist]], [[writer]] and [[social activist]]. Ozols\u2019 first book, the novel  \u201cLatvie\u0161i ir visur\u201d (\u201cLatvians are Everywhere\u201d) became a bestseller in 2011<ref>{{cite web |title=Latvian literature |url=http://latvianliterature.lv/en/writers/76 |website=Otto Ozols |publisher=Latvian literature |accessdate=25 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Kalni\u0146\u0161 |first1=P\u0113teris |title=Claiming Latvians are everywhere, sweeping novel proves entertaining |url=https://latviansonline.com/claiming-latvians-are-everywhere-sweeping-novel-proves-entertaining/ |website=Latvians online |accessdate=25 April 2020}}</ref>, having gone through 11 reprints since then. He has written two more books, \"Theodorus. Deja ar zilo\u0146zivi\" (\"Theodorus. Dancing with the Elephant Fish\"), published in 2014 and described as \u201cEurope's answer to Britain's James Bond and America's Jason Bourne\u201d, and \"Ne\u0113rt\u0101s paties\u012bbas\" (Uncomfortable truths), a collection of Ozols\u2019 opinion pieces and articles on Latvian politics, published in 2015. Otto Ozols is also an actively engaged author of political essays and political analysis, for several years he was a regular columnist for the largest news portals of Latvia, TVNET <ref>{{cite web |title=TVNET |url=https://www.tvnet.lv/author/112003 |website=TVNET |accessdate=25 April 2020}}</ref>, DELFI <ref>{{cite web |title=Delfi Latvija |url=https://www.delfi.lv/temas/otto-ozols/ |website=Delfi.lv |publisher=Delfi.lv |accessdate=25 April 2020}}</ref> and LA.lv <ref>{{cite web |title=LA |url=https://www.la.lv/author/otto-ozols |website=LA.LV |publisher=LA.LV |accessdate=25 April 2020}}</ref>.\n\n== Social activism ==\nIn order to acquaint himself with [[Catalonia\u2019s independence movement]], Otto Ozols in April 2016 became the first known person to traverse on foot the entire length of the [[Catalan Way]] \u2013 in 16 days, 480 km<ref>{{cite web |url=https://replay.lsm.lv/lv/ieraksts/lr/67564/rakstnieks-otto-ozols-katalonijas-cela |website=LSM.LV |accessdate=25 April 2020}}</ref>. Before doing this, he had written in September 2013 and article linking Catalan independence with the [[Baltic Way]] and Latvian Restoration Independence<ref>{{cite web |title=The Catalan Way (Via Catalana) is the way of tens of millions of Europeans |url=https://latviansonline.com/the-catalan-way-via-catalana-is-the-way-of-tens-of-millions-of-europeans/ |website=Latvians Online |accessdate=25 April 2020}}</ref>. He visited 68 villages and met with hundreds of individuals. In Barcelona, the capital city of Catalonia, he met with [[Carme Forcadell]], president of Catalonia\u2019s parliament at the time<ref>{{cite web |last1=Carme |first1=Forcadell |url=https://twitter.com/forcadellcarme/status/720542289483972608 |website=Twitter |publisher=Carme Forcadell |accessdate=25 April 2020}}</ref>. He is expected to publish a book of collected materials and impressions on his walking trip.\n\n== References ==\n", "name_user": "AbrahamBenJacob", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Otto_Ozols"}
{"title_page": "Wing (waltz)", "text_new": "A '''wing''' is a [[ballroom dance]] move, in the [[Waltz (International Standard)#Silver|silver syllabus]] of competition [[waltz]].  It is a transitional movement that repositions the follower to the leader's left side.  Thus, while many dance moves can precede a wing, only a reverse movement can follow a wing, such as a [[reverse turn]], [[double reverse spin]], [[Telemark (waltz)|Telemark]], fallaway reverse, or drag hesitation.\n\nThe wing begins with a forward hesitation while leading the woman to take three forward steps to the man's left side.  Thus, the next figure will begin in [[Glossary of partner dance terms#Outside partner position|outside partner position]], moving into a reverse turn.<ref name=\"BallroomDancers.com\">[http://www.ballroomdancers.com/Dances/info.asp?sid=500 BallroomDancers.com]</ref>\n\n==Footwork==\n\nThe wing may be preceded by any type of [[Whisk (ballroom dance)|whisk]], a [[chass\u00e9 from promenade position]], an [[open Telemark]], or an [[open impetus]].<ref>''The Ballroom Technique''; Moore, Alex (2006). Published by [[Imperial Society of Teachers of Dancing]]. ASIN: B000PH46KI.</ref>\n\n'''Leader (man)'''\n\n{| border=\"2\" cellpadding=\"4\" cellspacing=\"0\" style=\"margin: 1em 1em 1em 0; background: #f9f9f9; border: 1px #aaa solid; border-collapse: collapse; font-size: 90%;\"\n|-style=\"background:#B0C4DE;\"\n! Beat\n! Foot position\n! Alignment\n! Amount of turn\n! Footwork\n|-\n| 1\n| Right foot forward and across in [[promenade position]] (PP) and [[contra body movement position]] (CBMP)\n| Pointing to [[Direction of movement (dance)|line of dance]]\n| 1/8 between 3 and 1\n| Heel\n|-\n| 2\n| Left foot start to close to right foot\n| Towards facing diagonal center\n| body turn on 2\n| Pressure on toe of right foot with foot flat, and pressure on inside edge of toe of left foot\n|-\n| 3\n| Left foot closes to right foot without weight\n| Facing diagonal center\n| 1/8 between 2 and 3\n| Same as on beat 2\n|-\n|}\n\n'''Follower (lady)'''\n\n{| border=\"2\" cellpadding=\"4\" cellspacing=\"0\" style=\"margin: 1em 1em 1em 0; background: #f9f9f9; border: 1px #aaa solid; border-collapse: collapse; font-size: 90%;\"\n|-style=\"background:#B0C4DE;\"\n! Beat\n! Foot position\n! Alignment\n! Amount of turn\n! Footwork\n|-\n| 1\n| Left foot forward in [[Promenade position|PP]] and [[Contra body movement position|CBMP]]\n| Facing [[Direction of movement (dance)|diagonal center]]\n| 1/8 between 3 and 1\n| Heel \u2013 toe\n|-\n| 2\n| Right foot forward preparing to step [[Glossary of partner dance terms#Outside partner position|outside partner]] (OP) on left side\n| Facing center\n| 1/8 between 1 and 2\n| Toe\n|-\n| 3\n| Left foot forward in CBMP, OP on left side\n| Backing line of dance, continue to turn to backing diagonal center\n| 1/4 between 2 and 3, then continue to turn body to backing diagonal center\n| Toe \u2013 heel\n|-\n|}\n\n==Closed wing==\n\nThe closed wing is a [[Waltz (International Standard)#Gold|Gold syllabus]] step.  Whereas the regular wing ends in an outside partner position, the closed wing ends in [[closed position]].  Closed Wing may be preceded by a chass\u00e9 from promenade position, or an outside change.  It may be followed by a reverse turn or several variations of whisk.<ref name=\"BallroomDancers.com\"/>\n\n'''Leader (man)'''\n\n{| border=\"2\" cellpadding=\"4\" cellspacing=\"0\" style=\"margin: 1em 1em 1em 0; background: #f9f9f9; border: 1px #aaa solid; border-collapse: collapse; font-size: 90%;\"\n|-style=\"background:#B0C4DE;\"\n! Beat\n! Foot position\n! Alignment\n! Amount of turn\n! Footwork\n|-\n| 1\n| Right foot forward in [[Contra body movement position|CBMP]], [[Glossary of partner dance terms#Outside partner position|OP]]\n| Facing [[Direction of movement (dance)|diagonal center]]\n| \n| Heel\n|-\n| 2\n| Left foot starts to close to right foot\n| Facing diagonal center\n| Slight body turn to left on 2 and 3\n| Whole right foot, pressure on inside edge of toe of left foot\n|-\n| 3\n| Left foot closes to right foot without weight\n| Facing diagonal center\n| \n| Whole right foot, pressure on inside edge of toe of left foot\n|-\n|}\n\n'''Follower (lady)'''\n\n{| border=\"2\" cellpadding=\"4\" cellspacing=\"0\" style=\"margin: 1em 1em 1em 0; background: #f9f9f9; border: 1px #aaa solid; border-collapse: collapse; font-size: 90%;\"\n|-style=\"background:#B0C4DE;\"\n! Beat\n! Foot position\n! Alignment\n! Amount of turn\n! Footwork\n|-\n| 1\n| Left foot back in [[Contra body movement position|CBMP]]\n| Backing [[Direction of movement (dance)|diagonal center]]\n| \n| Toe \u2013 heel\n|-\n| 2\n| Right foot to side and slightly back (small step)\n| Backing diagonal center\n| \n| Toe\n|-\n| 3\n| Left foot forward in CBMP, [[Glossary of partner dance terms#Outside partner position|OP]] on left side\n| Facing diagonal wall against line of dance\n| Slight body turn to left\n| Toe \u2013 heel\n|-\n|}\n\n==References==\n\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Zy5trys-LOw Open Telemark and Wing demonstrated by Isaia Berardi and Cinzia Birarelli]\n\n{{Standard waltz}}\n\n[[Category:Waltz dance moves]]\n", "text_old": "A '''wing''' is a [[ballroom dance]] move, in the [[Waltz (International Standard)#Silver|silver syllabus]] of competition [[waltz]].  It is a transitional movement that repositions the follower to the leader's left side.  Thus, while many dance moves can precede a wing, only a reverse movement can follow a wing, such as a [[reverse turn]], [[double reverse spin]], [[Telemark (waltz)|Telemark]], fallaway reverse, or drag hesitation.\n\nThe wing begins with a forward hesitation while leading the woman to take three forward steps to the man's left side.  Thus, the next figure will begin in [[Glossary of partner dance terms#Outside partner position|outside partner position]], moving into a reverse turn.<ref name=\"BallroomDancers.com\">[http://www.ballroomdancers.com/Dances/info.asp?sid=500 BallroomDancers.com]</ref>\n\n==Footwork==\n\nThe wing may be preceded by any type of [[Whisk (ballroom dance)|whisk]], a [[chass\u00e9 from promenade position]], an [[open Telemark]], or an [[open impetus]].<ref>''The Ballroom Technique''; Moore, Alex (2006). Published by [[Imperial Society of Teachers of Dancing]]. ASIN: B000PH46KI.</ref>\n\n'''Leader (man)'''\n\n{| border=\"2\" cellpadding=\"4\" cellspacing=\"0\" style=\"margin: 1em 1em 1em 0; background: #f9f9f9; border: 1px #aaa solid; border-collapse: collapse; font-size: 90%;\"\n|-style=\"background:#B0C4DE;\"\n! Beat\n! Foot position\n! Alignment\n! Amount of turn\n! Footwork\n|-\n| 1\n| Right foot forward and across in [[promenade position]] (PP) and [[contra body movement position]] (CBMP)\n| Pointing to [[Direction of movement (dance)|line of dance]]\n| 1/8 between 3 and 1\n| Heel\n|-\n| 2\n| Left foot start to close to right foot\n| Towards facing diagonal center\n| body turn on 2\n| Pressure on toe of right foot with foot flat, and pressure on inside edge of toe (left foot)\n|-\n| 3\n| Left foot closes to right foot without weight\n| Facing diagonal center\n| 1/8 between 2 and 3\n| Same as step 2\n|-\n|}\n\n'''Follower (lady)'''\n\n{| border=\"2\" cellpadding=\"4\" cellspacing=\"0\" style=\"margin: 1em 1em 1em 0; background: #f9f9f9; border: 1px #aaa solid; border-collapse: collapse; font-size: 90%;\"\n|-style=\"background:#B0C4DE;\"\n! Beat\n! Foot position\n! Alignment\n! Amount of turn\n! Footwork\n|-\n| 1\n| Left foot forward in [[Promenade position|PP]] and [[Contra body movement position|CBMP]]\n| Facing [[Direction of movement (dance)|diagonal center]]\n| 1/8 between 3 and 1\n| Heel \u2013 toe\n|-\n| 2\n| Right foot forward preparing to step [[Glossary of partner dance terms#Outside partner position|outside partner]] (OP) on left side\n| Facing center\n| 1/8 between 1 and 2\n| Toe\n|-\n| 3\n| Left foot forward in CBMP, OP on left side\n| Backing line of dance, continue to turn to backing diagonal center\n| 1/4 between 2 and 3, then continue to turn body to backing diagonal center\n| Toe \u2013 heel\n|-\n|}\n\n==Closed wing==\n\nThe closed wing is a [[Waltz (International Standard)#Gold|Gold syllabus]] step.  Whereas the regular wing ends in an outside partner position, the closed wing ends in [[closed position]].  Closed Wing may be preceded by a chass\u00e9 from promenade position, or an outside change.  It may be followed by a reverse turn or several variations of whisk.<ref name=\"BallroomDancers.com\"/>\n\n'''Leader (man)'''\n\n{| border=\"2\" cellpadding=\"4\" cellspacing=\"0\" style=\"margin: 1em 1em 1em 0; background: #f9f9f9; border: 1px #aaa solid; border-collapse: collapse; font-size: 90%;\"\n|-style=\"background:#B0C4DE;\"\n! Beat\n! Foot position\n! Alignment\n! Amount of turn\n! Footwork\n|-\n| 1\n| Right foot forward in [[Contra body movement position|CBMP]], [[Glossary of partner dance terms#Outside partner position|OP]]\n| Facing [[Direction of movement (dance)|diagonal center]]\n| \n| Heel\n|-\n| 2\n| Left foot starts to close to right foot\n| Facing diagonal center\n| Slight body turn to left on 2 and 3\n| WF, pressure on inside edge of toe of left foot\n|-\n| 3\n| Left foot closes to Right foot w/o weight\n| Facing diagonal center\n| \n| WF, pressure on inside edge of toe of left foot\n|-\n|}\n\n'''Follower (lady)'''\n\n{| border=\"2\" cellpadding=\"4\" cellspacing=\"0\" style=\"margin: 1em 1em 1em 0; background: #f9f9f9; border: 1px #aaa solid; border-collapse: collapse; font-size: 90%;\"\n|-style=\"background:#B0C4DE;\"\n! Beat\n! Foot position\n! Alignment\n! Amount of turn\n! Footwork\n|-\n| 1\n| Left foot back in [[Contra body movement position|CBMP]]\n| Backing [[Direction of movement (dance)|diagonal center]]\n| \n| Toe \u2013 heel\n|-\n| 2\n| Right foot to side and slightly back (small step)\n| Backing diagonal center\n| \n| Toe\n|-\n| 3\n| Left foot forward in CBMP, [[Glossary of partner dance terms#Outside partner position|OP]] on left side\n| Facing diagonal wall against line of dance\n| Slight body turn to left\n| Toe \u2013 heel\n|-\n|}\n\n==References==\n\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Zy5trys-LOw Open Telemark and Wing demonstrated by Isaia Berardi and Cinzia Birarelli]\n\n{{Standard waltz}}\n\n[[Category:Waltz dance moves]]\n", "name_user": "Anypodetos", "label": "safe", "comment": "+", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wing_(waltz)"}
